# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: radar-systems
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:radar-systems/continuous-wave-radar] Doppler analysis of radar returns can allow the filtering out of slow or non-moving objects, thus offering immunity to interference from large stationary objects and slow-moving clutter.
[src:radar-systems/continuous-wave-radar] This makes it particularly useful for looking for objects against a background reflector, for instance, allowing a high-flying aircraft to look for aircraft flying at low altitudes against the background of the surface.
[src:radar-systems/continuous-wave-radar] Because the very strong reflection off the surface can be filtered out, the much smaller reflection from a target can still be seen.
[src:radar-systems/continuous-wave-radar] CW radar systems are used at both ends of the range spectrum.
[src:radar-systems/continuous-wave-radar] The main advantage of CW radar is that energy is not pulsed so these are much simpler to manufacture and operate.
[src:radar-systems/continuous-wave-radar] They have no minimum or maximum range, although the broadcast power level imposes a practical limit on range.
[src:radar-systems/continuous-wave-radar] Continuous-wave radar maximize total power on a target because the transmitter is broadcasting continuously.
[src:radar-systems/continuous-wave-radar] The military uses continuous-wave radar to guide semi-active radar homing (SARH) air-to-air missiles, such as the U.S.
[src:radar-systems/continuous-wave-radar] AIM-7 Sparrow and the Standard missile family.
[src:radar-systems/continuous-wave-radar] The launch aircraft *illuminates* the target with a CW radar signal, and the missile homes in on the reflected radio waves.
[src:radar-systems/continuous-wave-radar] Since the missile is moving at high velocities relative to the aircraft, there is a strong Doppler shift.
[src:radar-systems/continuous-wave-radar] Most modern air combat radars, even pulse Doppler sets, have a CW function for missile guidance purposes.
[src:radar-systems/continuous-wave-radar] Maximum distance in a continuous-wave radar is determined by the overall bandwidth and transmitter power.
[src:radar-systems/continuous-wave-radar] This bandwidth is determined by two factors.
[src:radar-systems/continuous-wave-radar] Doubling transmit power increases distance performance by about 20%.
[src:radar-systems/continuous-wave-radar] Reducing the total FM transmit noise by half has the same effect.
[src:radar-systems/continuous-wave-radar] Frequency domain receivers used for continuous-wave Doppler radar receivers are very different from conventional radar receivers.
[src:radar-systems/continuous-wave-radar] The receiver consists of a bank of filters, usually more than 100.
[src:radar-systems/continuous-wave-radar] The number of filters determines the maximum distance performance.
[src:radar-systems/continuous-wave-radar] Doubling the number of receiver filters increases distance performance by about 20%.
[src:radar-systems/continuous-wave-radar] Maximum distance performance is achieved when receiver filter size is equal to the maximum FM noise riding on the transmit signal.
[src:radar-systems/continuous-wave-radar] Reducing receiver filter size below average amount of FM transmit noise will not improve range performance.
[src:radar-systems/continuous-wave-radar] A CW radar is said to be *matched* when the receiver filter size matches the RMS bandwidth of the FM noise on the transmit signal.
[src:radar-systems/continuous-wave-radar] There are two types of continuous-wave radar: *unmodulated continuous-wave* and *modulated continuous-wave*.
[src:radar-systems/continuous-wave-radar] This kind of radar can cost less than $10 (2021).
[src:radar-systems/continuous-wave-radar] Return frequencies are shifted away from the transmitted frequency based on the Doppler effect when objects are moving.
[src:radar-systems/continuous-wave-radar] This type of radar is typically used with competition sports, like golf, tennis, baseball, NASCAR racing, and some smart-home appliances including light-bulbs and motion sensors.
[src:radar-systems/continuous-wave-radar] Continuous-wave radar without frequency modulation (FM) only detects moving targets, as stationary targets (along the line of sight) will not cause a Doppler shift.
[src:radar-systems/continuous-wave-radar] Reflected signals from stationary and slow-moving objects are masked by the transmit signal, which overwhelms reflections from slow-moving objects during normal operation.
[src:radar-systems/continuous-wave-radar] In this system the transmitted signal of a known stable frequency continuous wave varies up and down in frequency over a fixed period of time by a modulating signal.
[src:radar-systems/continuous-wave-radar] Frequency difference between the receive signal and the transmit signal increases with delay, and hence with distance.
[src:radar-systems/continuous-wave-radar] This smears out, or blurs, the Doppler signal.
[src:radar-systems/continuous-wave-radar] Echoes from a target are then mixed with the transmitted signal to produce a beat signal which will give the distance of the target after demodulation.
[src:radar-systems/continuous-wave-radar] Range demodulation is limited to a quarter wavelength of the transmit modulation.
[src:radar-systems/continuous-wave-radar] Instrumented range for 100 Hz FM would be 500 km.
[src:radar-systems/continuous-wave-radar] That limit depends upon the type of modulation and demodulation.
[src:radar-systems/continuous-wave-radar] The radar will report incorrect distance for reflections from distances beyond the instrumented range, such as from the moon.
[src:radar-systems/continuous-wave-radar] FMCW range measurements are only reliable to about 60% of the instrumented range, or about 300 km for 100 Hz FM.
[src:radar-systems/continuous-wave-radar] Sawtooth modulation is the most used in FM-CW radars where range is desired for objects that lack rotating parts.
[src:radar-systems/continuous-wave-radar] Range information is mixed with the Doppler velocity using this technique.
[src:radar-systems/continuous-wave-radar] Modulation can be turned off on alternate scans to identify velocity using unmodulated carrier frequency shift.
[src:radar-systems/continuous-wave-radar] This allows range and velocity to be found with one radar set.
[src:radar-systems/continuous-wave-radar] Triangle wave modulation can be used to achieve the same goal.
[src:radar-systems/continuous-wave-radar] As shown in the figure, the received waveform (green) is simply a delayed replica of the transmitted waveform (red).
[src:radar-systems/continuous-wave-radar] The transmitted frequency is used to down-convert the receive signal to baseband, and the amount of frequency shift between the transmit signal and the reflected signal increases with time delay (distance).
[src:radar-systems/continuous-wave-radar] The time delay is thus a measure of the range; a small frequency spread is produced by nearby reflections, a larger frequency spread corresponds with more time delay and a longer range.
[src:radar-systems/continuous-wave-radar] With the advent of modern electronics, digital signal processing is used for most detection processing.
[src:radar-systems/continuous-wave-radar] The beat signals are passed through an analog-to-digital converter, and digital processing is performed on the result.
[src:radar-systems/continuous-wave-radar] The transmit signal $x(t)$ of a saw-tooth FM-CW radar consists of one or multiple ramps (see figure).
[src:radar-systems/continuous-wave-radar] A single ramp starts with a frequency $f_{0}$ and increases linearly with slope $\alpha$ .
[src:radar-systems/continuous-wave-radar] The ramp ends after a duration T and has covered a bandwidth $B=\alpha T$ .
[src:radar-systems/continuous-wave-radar] During the time of a single ramp, the transmit signal is a scaled cosine.
[src:radar-systems/continuous-wave-radar] The radar receives the signal $y(t)$ which is a sum of K damped and delayed versions of the signal $x(t)$ .
[src:radar-systems/continuous-wave-radar] The delays $\tau _{k}$ denote the time a signal travels form the radar to an object and back to the radar.
[src:radar-systems/continuous-wave-radar] The radar mixes (multiplies) the received signal $y(t)$ with the transmitted signal $x(t)$ and applies a low-pass filter.
[src:radar-systems/continuous-wave-radar] The resulting ″deramped″ signal can be approximated as a sum of cosines.
[src:radar-systems/continuous-wave-radar] Each of these cosines corresponds to a path that the signal travelled from the radar to an object and back to the radar.
[src:radar-systems/continuous-wave-radar] The frequencies $f_{\mathrm {b} ,k}$ are called *beat frequencies*.
[src:radar-systems/continuous-wave-radar] The beat frequencies depend on the distance (range) $r_{k}$ between radar and object k , on the speed of light, on the slope $\alpha$ , the relative velocity $v_{k}$ of object k with respect to the radar, and on the carrier frequency $f_{\mathrm {c} }=f_{0}+B/2$ .
[src:radar-systems/continuous-wave-radar] Since the beat frequency contains the distance $r_{k}$ to the object and the velocity $v_{k}$ of the object, it is in general not possible to separate both quantities from a single transmitted saw-tooth only.
[src:radar-systems/continuous-wave-radar] As described above, the deramped signal is a superposition of cosines.
[src:radar-systems/continuous-wave-radar] This results in an inherent ambiguity in the distance estimation (now assuming non-moving objects).
[src:radar-systems/continuous-wave-radar] According to the Nyquist–Shannon sampling theorem, the maximum frequency that can be recovered after sampling is half the sampling frequency $f_{\mathrm {S} }$ .
[src:radar-systems/continuous-wave-radar] Hence, the maximum beat frequency that can be observed after sampling is $f_{\mathrm {b} ,\mathrm {max} }=f_{\mathrm {S} }/2$ .
[src:radar-systems/continuous-wave-radar] This translates into maximum range $r_{\mathrm {max} }$ .
[src:radar-systems/continuous-wave-radar] This ambiguity is called the *maximum unambiguous range*.
[src:radar-systems/continuous-wave-radar] The maximum unambiguous range depends on the sampling frequency $f_{\mathrm {S} }$ , on the speed of light $c'$ , and on the frequency slope $\alpha$ (or equivalently on the length T of the saw-tooth and the covered bandwidth B ).
[src:radar-systems/continuous-wave-radar] Without any additional information, an FM-CW radar with saw-tooth frequency modulation cannot distinguish between a distance r and a distance $r'=r+nr_{\mathrm {max} }$ , for any integer n .
[src:radar-systems/continuous-wave-radar] Both distances would result in the same beat frequency.
[src:radar-systems/continuous-wave-radar] Usually, it is just assumed that only ranges $r=0\ldots r_{\mathrm {max} }$ are present.
[src:radar-systems/continuous-wave-radar] For practical reasons, receive samples are not processed for a brief period after the modulation ramp begins because incoming reflections will have modulation from the previous modulation cycle.
[src:radar-systems/continuous-wave-radar] This imposes a range limit and limits performance.
[src:radar-systems/continuous-wave-radar] Sinusoidal FM is used when both range and velocity are required simultaneously for complex objects with multiple moving parts like turbine fan blades, helicopter blades, or propellers.
[src:radar-systems/continuous-wave-radar] This processing reduces the effect of complex spectra modulation produced by rotating parts that introduce errors into range measurement process.
[src:radar-systems/continuous-wave-radar] This technique also has the advantage that the receiver never needs to stop processing incoming signals because the modulation waveform is continuous with no impulse modulation.
[src:radar-systems/continuous-wave-radar] Sinusoidal FM is eliminated by the receiver for close in reflections because the transmit frequency will be the same as the frequency being reflected back into the receiver.
[src:radar-systems/continuous-wave-radar] The spectrum for more distant objects will contain more modulation.
[src:radar-systems/continuous-wave-radar] The amount of spectrum spreading caused by modulation riding on the receive signal is proportional to the distance to the reflecting object.
[src:radar-systems/continuous-wave-radar] A time delay is introduced in transit between the radar and the reflector.
[src:radar-systems/continuous-wave-radar] The detection process down converts the receive signal using the transmit signal.
[src:radar-systems/continuous-wave-radar] Receiver demodulation is used with FMCW similar to the receiver demodulation strategy used with pulse compression.
[src:radar-systems/continuous-wave-radar] This takes place before Doppler CFAR detection processing.
[src:radar-systems/continuous-wave-radar] A large modulation index is needed for practical reasons.
[src:radar-systems/continuous-wave-radar] Practical systems introduce reverse FM on the receive signal using digital signal processing before the fast Fourier transform process is used to produce the spectrum.
[src:radar-systems/continuous-wave-radar] This is repeated with several different demodulation values.
[src:radar-systems/continuous-wave-radar] Range is found by identifying the receive spectrum where width is minimum.
[src:radar-systems/continuous-wave-radar] Practical systems also process receive samples for several cycles of the FM in order to reduce the influence of sampling artifacts.
[src:radar-systems/continuous-wave-radar] There are two different antenna configurations used with continuous-wave radar: *monostatic radar*, and *bistatic radar*.
[src:radar-systems/continuous-wave-radar] The radar receive antenna is located nearby the radar transmit antenna in monostatic radar.
[src:radar-systems/continuous-wave-radar] Feed-through null is typically required to eliminate bleed-through between the transmitter and receiver to increase sensitivity in practical systems.
[src:radar-systems/continuous-wave-radar] This is typically used with continuous-wave angle tracking (CWAT) radar receivers that are interoperable with surface-to-air missile systems.
[src:radar-systems/continuous-wave-radar] Interrupted continuous-wave can be used to eliminate bleed-through between the transmit and receive antenna.
[src:radar-systems/continuous-wave-radar] This kind of system typically takes one sample between each pair of transmit pulses, and the sample rate is typically 30 kHz or more.
[src:radar-systems/continuous-wave-radar] This technique is used with the least expensive kinds of radar, such as those used for traffic monitoring and sports.
[src:radar-systems/continuous-wave-radar] FM-CW radars can be built with one antenna using either a circulator, or circular polarization.
[src:radar-systems/continuous-wave-radar] The radar receive antenna is located far from the radar transmit antenna in bistatic radar.
[src:radar-systems/continuous-wave-radar] The transmitter is fairly expensive, while the receiver is fairly inexpensive and disposable.
[src:radar-systems/continuous-wave-radar] This is typically used with semi-active radar homing including most surface-to-air missile systems.
[src:radar-systems/continuous-wave-radar] The transmit radar is typically located near the missile launcher.
[src:radar-systems/continuous-wave-radar] The transmit antenna illuminates the target in much the same way as a search light.
[src:radar-systems/continuous-wave-radar] The transmit antenna also issues an omnidirectional sample.
[src:radar-systems/continuous-wave-radar] The receiver uses two antennas – one antenna aimed at the target and one antenna aimed at the transmit antenna.
[src:radar-systems/continuous-wave-radar] The receive antenna that is aimed at the transmit antenna is used to develop the feed-through null, which allows the target receiver to operate reliably in or near the main beam of the antenna.
[src:radar-systems/continuous-wave-radar] The bistatic FM-CW receiver and transmitter pair may also take the form of an over-the-air deramping (OTAD) system.
[src:radar-systems/continuous-wave-radar] An OTAD transmitter broadcasts an FM-CW signal on two different frequency channels; one for synchronisation of the receiver with the transmitter, the other for illuminating the measurement scene.
[src:radar-systems/continuous-wave-radar] Using directive antennas, the OTAD receiver collects both signals simultaneously and mixes the synchronisation signal with the downconverted echo signal from the measurement scene in a process known as over-the-air deramping.
[src:radar-systems/continuous-wave-radar] The frequency of deramped signal is proportional to the bistatic range to the target less the baseline distance between the OTAD transmitter and the OTAD receiver.
[src:radar-systems/continuous-wave-radar] Most modern systems FM-CW radars use one transmitter antenna and multiple receiver antennas.
[src:radar-systems/continuous-wave-radar] Because the transmitter is on continuously at effectively the same frequency as the receiver, special care must be exercised to avoid overloading the receiver stages.
[src:radar-systems/continuous-wave-radar] Monopulse antennas produce angular measurements without pulses or other modulation.
[src:radar-systems/continuous-wave-radar] This technique is used in semi-active radar homing.
[src:radar-systems/continuous-wave-radar] The transmit signal will leak into the receiver on practical systems.
[src:radar-systems/continuous-wave-radar] Significant leakage will come from nearby environmental reflections even if antenna components are perfect.
[src:radar-systems/continuous-wave-radar] As much as 120 dB of leakage rejection is required to achieve acceptable performance.
[src:radar-systems/continuous-wave-radar] Three approaches can be used to produce a practical system that will function correctly.
[src:radar-systems/continuous-wave-radar] Null and filter approaches must be used with bistatic radar, like semi-active radar homing, for practical reasons because side-lobes from the illumination radar will illuminate the environment in addition to the main-lobe illumination on the target.
[src:radar-systems/continuous-wave-radar] Similar constraints apply to ground-based CW radar.
[src:radar-systems/continuous-wave-radar] Interruption applies to cheap hand held mono-static radar systems (police radar and sporting goods).
[src:radar-systems/continuous-wave-radar] This is impractical for bistatic systems because of the cost and complexity associated with coordinating time with nanosecond precision in two different locations.
[src:radar-systems/continuous-wave-radar] The design constraint that drives this requirement is the dynamic range limitation of practical receiver components that include band pass filters that take time to settle out.
[src:radar-systems/continuous-wave-radar] The actual transmit signal is rotated 180 degrees, attenuated, and fed into the receiver.
[src:radar-systems/continuous-wave-radar] The phase shift and attenuation are set using feedback obtained from the receiver to cancel most of the leakage.
[src:radar-systems/continuous-wave-radar] Typical improvement is on the order of 30 dB to 70 dB.
[src:radar-systems/continuous-wave-radar] The filter approach relies on using a very narrow band reject filter that will eliminate low velocity signals from nearby reflectors.
[src:radar-systems/continuous-wave-radar] The band reject area spans 10 mile per hour to 100 mile per hour depending upon the anticipated environment.
[src:radar-systems/continuous-wave-radar] While interrupted carrier systems are not considered to be CW systems, performance characteristics are sufficiently similar to group interrupted CW systems with pure CW radar because the pulse rate is high enough that range measurements cannot be done without frequency modulation (FM).
[src:radar-systems/continuous-wave-radar] This technique turns the transmitter off for a period before receiver sampling begins.
[src:radar-systems/continuous-wave-radar] Receiver interference declines by about 8.7 dB per time constant.
[src:radar-systems/continuous-wave-radar] Leakage reduction of 120 dB requires 14 recover bandwidth time constants between when the transmitter is turned off and receiver sampling begins.
[src:radar-systems/continuous-wave-radar] The interruption concept is widely used, especially in long-range radar applications where the receiver sensitivity is very important.
[src:radar-systems/continuous-wave-radar] It is commonly known as "frequency modulated interrupted continuous wave", or FMICW.
[src:radar-systems/continuous-wave-radar] Because of simplicity, CW radar are inexpensive to manufacture, relatively free from failure, cheap to maintain, and fully automated.
[src:radar-systems/continuous-wave-radar] Some are small enough to carry in a pocket.
[src:radar-systems/continuous-wave-radar] More sophisticated CW radar systems can reliably achieve accurate detections exceeding 100 km distance while providing missile illumination.
[src:radar-systems/continuous-wave-radar] The FMCW ramp can be compressed providing extra signal to noise gains such one does not need the extra power that pulse radar using a no FM modulation would.
[src:radar-systems/continuous-wave-radar] This combined with the fact that it is coherent means that Fourier integration can be used rather than azimuth integration providing superior signal to noise and a Doppler measurement.
[src:radar-systems/continuous-wave-radar] Doppler processing allows signal integration between successive receiver samples.
[src:radar-systems/continuous-wave-radar] This means that the number of samples can be increased to extend the detection range without increasing transmit power.
[src:radar-systems/continuous-wave-radar] That technique can be used to produce inexpensive stealthy low-power radar.
[src:radar-systems/continuous-wave-radar] CW performance is similar to pulse-Doppler radar performance for this reason.
[src:radar-systems/continuous-wave-radar] Unmodulated continuous wave radar cannot measure distance.
[src:radar-systems/continuous-wave-radar] Signal amplitude provides the only way to determine which object corresponds with which speed measurement when there is more than one moving object near the receiver, but amplitude information is not useful without range measurement to evaluate target size.
[src:radar-systems/continuous-wave-radar] Moving objects include birds flying near objects in front of the antenna.
[src:radar-systems/continuous-wave-radar] Small radar systems that lack range modulation are only reliable when used with one object in a sterile environment free from vegetation, aircraft, birds, weather phenomenon, and other nearby vehicles.
[src:radar-systems/continuous-wave-radar] With 20 dB antenna side-lobes, a truck or tree with 1,000 square feet of reflecting surface behind the antenna can produce a signal as strong as a car with 10 square feet of reflecting in front of a small hand held antenna.
[src:radar-systems/continuous-wave-radar] An area survey is required to determine if hand held devices will operate reliably because unobserved roadway traffic and trees behind the operator can interfere with observations made in front of the operator.
[src:radar-systems/continuous-wave-radar] This is a typical problem with radar speed guns used by law enforcement officers, NASCAR events, and sports, like baseball, golf, and tennis.
[src:radar-systems/continuous-wave-radar] Interference from a second radar, automobile ignition, other moving objects, moving fan blades on the intended target, and other radio frequency sources will corrupt measurements.
[src:radar-systems/continuous-wave-radar] These systems are limited by wavelength, which is 0.02 meter at Ku band, so the beam spread exceeds 45 degrees if the antenna is smaller than 12 inches (0.3 meter).
[src:radar-systems/continuous-wave-radar] Significant antenna side-lobes extend in all directions unless the antenna is larger than the vehicle on which the radar is mounted.
[src:radar-systems/continuous-wave-radar] Side-lobe suppression and FM range modulation are required for reliable operation.
[src:radar-systems/continuous-wave-radar] There is no way to know the direction of the arriving signal without side-lobe suppression, which requires two or more antennae, each with its own individual receiver.
[src:radar-systems/continuous-wave-radar] There is no way to know distance without FM range modulation.
[src:radar-systems/continuous-wave-radar] Speed, direction, and distance are all required to pick out an individual object.
[src:radar-systems/continuous-wave-radar] These limitations are due to the well known limitations of basic physics that cannot be overcome by design.
[src:radar-systems/phased-array] In antenna theory, a **phased array** usually means an **electronically scanned array**, a computer-controlled array of antennas which creates a beam of radio waves that can be electronically steered to point in different directions without moving the antennas.
[src:radar-systems/phased-array] In a phased array, the power from the transmitter is fed to the radiating elements through devices called *phase shifters*, controlled by a computer system, which can alter the phase or signal delay electronically, thus steering the beam of radio waves to a different direction.
[src:radar-systems/phased-array] Since the size of an antenna array must extend many wavelengths to achieve the high gain needed for narrow beamwidth, phased arrays are mainly practical at the high frequency end of the radio spectrum, in the UHF and microwave bands, in which the operating wavelengths are conveniently small.
[src:radar-systems/phased-array] Phased arrays were originally invented for use in military radar systems, to detect fast moving planes and missiles, but are now widely used and have spread to civilian applications such as 5G MIMO for cell phones.
[src:radar-systems/phased-array] The phased array principle is also used in acoustics in such applications as phased array ultrasonics, and in optics.
[src:radar-systems/phased-array] The term "phased array" is also used to a lesser extent for unsteered array antennas in which the radiation pattern of the antenna array is fixed.
[src:radar-systems/phased-array] For example, AM broadcast radio antennas consisting of multiple mast radiators are also called "phased arrays".
[src:radar-systems/phased-array] A phased array is an **electronically scanned array**, a computer-controlled array of antennas which creates a beam of radio waves that can be electronically steered to point in different directions without moving the antennas.
[src:radar-systems/phased-array] The general theory of an electromagnetic phased array also finds applications in ultrasonic and medical imaging application (*phased array ultrasonics*) and in optics (*optical phased array*).
[src:radar-systems/phased-array] In a simple array antenna, the radio frequency current from the transmitter is fed to multiple individual antenna elements with the proper phase relationship so that the radio waves from the separate elements combine (superpose) to form beams.
[src:radar-systems/phased-array] This can be configured to increase power radiated in desired directions and suppress radiation in undesired directions.
[src:radar-systems/phased-array] In a phased array, the power from the transmitter is fed to the radiating elements through devices called *phase shifters*, controlled by a computer system.
[src:radar-systems/phased-array] The computer can alter the phase or signal delay of each antenna element electronically, resulting in a beam of radio waves that can be dynamically "steered" to propagate in arbitrary directions.
[src:radar-systems/phased-array] Phased arrays were originally conceived for use in military radar systems, to steer a beam of radio waves quickly across the sky to detect planes and missiles.
[src:radar-systems/phased-array] These systems are now widely used and have spread to civilian applications such as 5G MIMO for cell phones.
[src:radar-systems/phased-array] The phased array principle is also used in acoustics, and phased arrays of acoustic transducers are used in medical ultrasound imaging scanners (phased array ultrasonics), oil and gas prospecting (reflection seismology), and military sonar systems.
[src:radar-systems/phased-array] The term "phased array" is also used to a lesser extent for non steerable array antennas in which the phase of the feed power and thus the radiation pattern of the antenna array is fixed.
[src:radar-systems/phased-array] For example, AM broadcast radio antennas consisting of multiple mast radiators fed so as to create a specific radiation pattern are also called "phased arrays".
[src:radar-systems/phased-array] However, the four most common are the passive electronically scanned array (PESA), active electronically scanned array (AESA), hybrid beam forming phased array, and digital beam forming (DBF) array.
[src:radar-systems/phased-array] A *passive phased array* or *passive electronically scanned array* (PESA) is a phased array in which the antenna elements are connected to a single transmitter and/or receiver, as shown in the first animation at top.
[src:radar-systems/phased-array] PESAs are the most common type of phased array.
[src:radar-systems/phased-array] Generally speaking, a PESA uses one receiver/exciter for the entire array.
[src:radar-systems/phased-array] An *active phased array* or *active electronically scanned array* (AESA) is a phased array in which each antenna element has an analog transmitter/receiver (T/R) module which creates the phase shifting required to electronically steer the antenna beam.
[src:radar-systems/phased-array] Active arrays are a more advanced, second-generation phased-array technology that are used in military applications; unlike PESAs they can radiate several beams of radio waves at multiple frequencies in different directions simultaneously.
[src:radar-systems/phased-array] However, the number of simultaneous beams is limited by practical reasons of electronic packaging of the beam formers to approximately three simultaneous beams for an AESA.
[src:radar-systems/phased-array] Each beam former has a receiver/exciter connected to it.
[src:radar-systems/phased-array] A *digital beam forming (DBF) phased array* has a digital receiver/exciter at each element in the array.
[src:radar-systems/phased-array] The signal at each element is digitized by the receiver/exciter.
[src:radar-systems/phased-array] This means that antenna beams can be formed digitally in a field programmable gate array (FPGA) or the array computer.
[src:radar-systems/phased-array] This approach allows for multiple simultaneous antenna beams to be formed.
[src:radar-systems/phased-array] A *hybrid beam forming phased array* can be thought of as a combination of an AESA and a digital beam forming phased array.
[src:radar-systems/phased-array] It uses subarrays that are active phased arrays (for instance, a subarray may be 64, 128 or 256 elements and the number of elements depends upon system requirements).
[src:radar-systems/phased-array] The subarrays are combined to form the full array.
[src:radar-systems/phased-array] Each subarray has its own digital receiver/exciter.
[src:radar-systems/phased-array] This approach allows clusters of simultaneous beams to be created.
[src:radar-systems/phased-array] A *conformal antenna* is a phased array in which the individual antennas, instead of being arranged in a flat plane, are mounted on a curved surface.
[src:radar-systems/phased-array] The phase shifters compensate for the different path lengths of the waves due to the antenna elements' varying position on the surface, allowing the array to radiate a plane wave.
[src:radar-systems/phased-array] Conformal antennas are used in aircraft and missiles, to integrate the antenna into the curving surface of the aircraft to reduce aerodynamic drag.
[src:radar-systems/phased-array] There are two main types of beamformers.
[src:radar-systems/phased-array] These are time domain beamformers and frequency domain beamformers.
[src:radar-systems/phased-array] From a theoretical point of view, both are in principle the same operation, with just a Fourier transform allowing conversion from one to the other type.
[src:radar-systems/phased-array] A graduated attenuation window is sometimes applied across the face of the array to improve side-lobe suppression performance, in addition to the phase shift.
[src:radar-systems/phased-array] Time domain beamformer works by introducing time delays.
[src:radar-systems/phased-array] The basic operation is called "delay and sum".
[src:radar-systems/phased-array] It delays the incoming signal from each array element by a certain amount of time, and then adds them together.
[src:radar-systems/phased-array] A Butler matrix allows several beams to be formed simultaneously, or one beam to be scanned through an arc.
[src:radar-systems/phased-array] The most common kind of time domain beam former is serpentine waveguide.
[src:radar-systems/phased-array] Active phased array designs use individual delay lines that are switched on and off.
[src:radar-systems/phased-array] Yttrium iron garnet phase shifters vary the phase delay using the strength of a magnetic field.
[src:radar-systems/phased-array] There are two different types of frequency domain beamformers.
[src:radar-systems/phased-array] The first type separates the different frequency components that are present in the received signal into multiple frequency bins (using either a Discrete Fourier transform (DFT) or a filterbank).
[src:radar-systems/phased-array] When different delay and sum beamformers are applied to each frequency bin, the result is that the main lobe simultaneously points in multiple different directions at each of the different frequencies.
[src:radar-systems/phased-array] This can be an advantage for communication links, and is used with the SPS-48 radar.
[src:radar-systems/phased-array] The other type of frequency domain beamformer makes use of Spatial Frequency.
[src:radar-systems/phased-array] Discrete samples are taken from each of the individual array elements.
[src:radar-systems/phased-array] The DFT introduces multiple different discrete phase shifts during processing.
[src:radar-systems/phased-array] The outputs of the DFT are individual channels that correspond with evenly spaced beams formed simultaneously.
[src:radar-systems/phased-array] A 1-dimensional DFT produces a fan of different beams.
[src:radar-systems/phased-array] A 2-dimensional DFT produces beams with a pineapple configuration.
[src:radar-systems/phased-array] These techniques are used to create two kinds of phased array.
[src:radar-systems/phased-array] There are two further sub-categories that modify the kind of dynamic array or fixed array.
[src:radar-systems/phased-array] Each array element incorporates an adjustable phase shifter.
[src:radar-systems/phased-array] These are collectively used to move the beam with respect to the array face.
[src:radar-systems/phased-array] Dynamic phased arrays require no physical movement to aim the beam.
[src:radar-systems/phased-array] This can produce antenna motion fast enough to use a small pencil beam to simultaneously track multiple targets while searching for new targets using just one radar set, a capability known as *track while search*.
[src:radar-systems/phased-array] As an example, an antenna with a 2-degree beam with a pulse rate of 1 kHz will require approximately 8 seconds to cover an entire hemisphere consisting of 8,000 pointing positions.
[src:radar-systems/phased-array] This configuration provides 12 opportunities to detect a 1,000 m/s (2,200 mph; 3,600 km/h) vehicle over a range of 100 km (62 mi), which is suitable for military applications.
[src:radar-systems/phased-array] The position of mechanically steered antennas can be predicted, which can be used to create electronic countermeasures that interfere with radar operation.
[src:radar-systems/phased-array] The flexibility resulting from phased array operation allows beams to be aimed at random locations, which eliminates this vulnerability.
[src:radar-systems/phased-array] This is also desirable for military applications.
[src:radar-systems/phased-array] Fixed phased array antennas are typically used to create an antenna with a more desirable form factor than the conventional parabolic reflector or cassegrain reflector.
[src:radar-systems/phased-array] Fixed phased arrays incorporate fixed phase shifters.
[src:radar-systems/phased-array] For example, most commercial FM Radio and TV antenna towers use a collinear antenna array, which is a fixed phased array of dipole elements.
[src:radar-systems/phased-array] In radar applications, this kind of phased array is physically moved during the track and scan process.
[src:radar-systems/phased-array] The SPS-48 radar uses multiple transmit frequencies with a serpentine delay line along the left side of the array to produce vertical fan of stacked beams.
[src:radar-systems/phased-array] Each frequency experiences a different phase shift as it propagates down the serpentine delay line, which forms different beams.
[src:radar-systems/phased-array] A filter bank is used to split apart the individual receive beams.
[src:radar-systems/phased-array] Semi-active radar homing uses monopulse radar that relies on a fixed phased array to produce multiple adjacent beams that measure angle errors.
[src:radar-systems/phased-array] This form factor is suitable for gimbal mounting in missile seekers.
[src:radar-systems/phased-array] Active electronically-scanned arrays (AESA) elements incorporate transmit amplification with phase shift in each antenna element (or group of elements).
[src:radar-systems/phased-array] Each element also includes receive pre-amplification.
[src:radar-systems/phased-array] The phase shifter setting is the same for transmit and receive.
[src:radar-systems/phased-array] Active phased arrays do not require phase reset after the end of the transmit pulse, which is compatible with Doppler radar and pulse-Doppler radar.
[src:radar-systems/phased-array] Passive phased arrays typically use large amplifiers that produce all of the microwave transmit signal for the antenna.
[src:radar-systems/phased-array] Phase shifters typically consist of waveguide elements controlled by magnetic field, voltage gradient, or equivalent technology.
[src:radar-systems/phased-array] The phase shift process used with passive phased arrays typically puts the receive beam and transmit beam into diagonally opposite quadrants.
[src:radar-systems/phased-array] The sign of the phase shift must be inverted after the transmit pulse is finished and before the receive period begins to place the receive beam into the same location as the transmit beam.
[src:radar-systems/phased-array] That requires a phase impulse that degrades sub-clutter visibility performance on Doppler radar and Pulse-Doppler radar.
[src:radar-systems/phased-array] As an example, Yttrium iron garnet phase shifters must be changed after transmit pulse quench and before receiver processing starts to align transmit and receive beams.
[src:radar-systems/phased-array] That impulse introduces FM noise that degrades clutter performance.
[src:radar-systems/phased-array] Passive phased array design is used in the AEGIS Combat System for direction-of-arrival estimation.
[src:radar-systems/phased-array] ballistic missile detection radar in Alaska.
[src:radar-systems/phased-array] Completed in 1979, it was one of the first active phased arrays.
[src:radar-systems/phased-array] Closeup of some of the 2677 crossed dipole antenna elements that make up the plane array.
[src:radar-systems/phased-array] This antenna produced a narrow "pencil" beam only 2.2° wide.
[src:radar-systems/phased-array] Phased array transmission was originally shown in 1905 by Nobel laureate Karl Ferdinand Braun who demonstrated enhanced transmission of radio waves in one direction.
[src:radar-systems/phased-array] During World War II, Nobel laureate Luis Alvarez used phased array transmission in a rapidly steerable radar system for "ground-controlled approach", a system to aid in the landing of aircraft.
[src:radar-systems/phased-array] At the same time, the German GEMA company (German for *Gesellschaft für elektroakustische und mechanische Apparate*) built the Mammut 1.
[src:radar-systems/phased-array] It was later adapted for radio astronomy leading to Nobel Prizes for Physics for Antony Hewish and Martin Ryle after several large phased arrays were developed at the University of Cambridge Interplanetary Scintillation Array.
[src:radar-systems/phased-array] This design is also used for radar, and is generalized in interferometric radio antennas.
[src:radar-systems/phased-array] In 1966, most phased-array radars use ferrite phase shifters or traveling-wave tubes to dynamically adjust the phase.
[src:radar-systems/phased-array] The AN/SPS-33 -- installed on the nuclear-powered ships Long Beach and Enterprise around 1961 -- was claimed to be the only operational 3-D phased array in the world in 1966.
[src:radar-systems/phased-array] The AN/SPG-59 was designed to generate multiple tracking beams from the transmitting array and simultaneously program independent receiving arrays.
[src:radar-systems/phased-array] The first civilian 3D phased array was built in 1960 at the National Aviation Facilities Experimental Center; but was abandoned in 1961.
[src:radar-systems/phased-array] In 2004, Caltech researchers demonstrated the first integrated silicon-based phased array receiver at 24 GHz with 8 elements.
[src:radar-systems/phased-array] This was followed by their demonstration of a CMOS 24 GHz phased array transmitter in 2005 and a fully integrated 77 GHz phased array transceiver with integrated antennas in 2006 by the Caltech team.
[src:radar-systems/phased-array] In 2007, DARPA researchers announced a 16-element phased-array radar antenna which was also integrated with all the necessary circuits on a single silicon chip and operated at 30–50 GHz.
[src:radar-systems/phased-array] The relative amplitudes of—and constructive and destructive interference effects among—the signals radiated by the individual antennas determine the effective radiation pattern of the array.
[src:radar-systems/phased-array] A phased array may be used to point a fixed radiation pattern, or to scan rapidly in azimuth or elevation.
[src:radar-systems/phased-array] Simultaneous electrical scanning in both azimuth and elevation was first demonstrated in a phased array antenna at Hughes Aircraft Company, California in 1957.
[src:radar-systems/phased-array] The total directivity of a phased array will be a result of the gain of the individual array elements, and the directivity due their positioning in an array.
[src:radar-systems/phased-array] This latter component is closely tied to, but not equal to, the array factor.
[src:radar-systems/phased-array] Here, $\theta$ and $\phi$ are the directions which we are taking the array factor in, in the coordinate frame depicted to the right.
[src:radar-systems/phased-array] The factors $\beta _{x}$ and $\beta _{y}$ are the *progressive phase shift* that is used to steer the beam electronically.
[src:radar-systems/phased-array] The factors $I_{n1}$ and $I_{m1}$ are the excitation coefficients of the individual elements.
[src:radar-systems/phased-array] In all above equations, the value k describes the wavenumber of the frequency used in transmission.
[src:radar-systems/phased-array] These equations can be solved to predict the nulls, main lobe, and grating lobes of the array.
[src:radar-systems/phased-array] It is common in engineering to provide phased array $AF$ values in decibels through $AF_{dB}=10\log _{10}AF$ .
[src:radar-systems/phased-array] Recalling the complex exponential in the array factor equation above, often, what is *really* meant by array factor is the magnitude of the summed phasor produced at the end of array factor calculation.
[src:radar-systems/phased-array] This represents a coordinate frame whose $\mathbf {x}$ axis is aligned with the array $\mathbf {z}$ axis, and whose $\mathbf {y}$ axis is aligned with the array $\mathbf {x}$ axis.
[src:radar-systems/phased-array] These values have been clipped to have a minimum $AF$ of -50 dB, however, in reality, null points in the array factor pattern will have values significantly smaller than this.
[src:radar-systems/phased-array] Phased arrays were invented for radar tracking of ballistic missiles, and because of their fast tracking abilities phased array radars are widely used in military applications.
[src:radar-systems/phased-array] For example, because of the rapidity with which the beam can be steered, phased array radars allow a warship to use one radar system for surface detection and tracking (finding ships), air detection and tracking (finding aircraft and missiles) and missile uplink capabilities.
[src:radar-systems/phased-array] Before using these systems, each surface-to-air missile in flight required a dedicated fire-control radar, which meant that radar-guided weapons could only engage a small number of simultaneous targets.
[src:radar-systems/phased-array] Phased array systems can be used to control missiles during the mid-course phase of the missile's flight.
[src:radar-systems/phased-array] During the terminal portion of the flight, continuous-wave fire control directors provide the final guidance to the target.
[src:radar-systems/phased-array] Because the antenna pattern is electronically steered, phased array systems can direct radar beams fast enough to maintain a fire control quality track on many targets simultaneously while also controlling several in-flight missiles.
[src:radar-systems/phased-array] The German Navy and the Royal Dutch Navy have developed the Active Phased Array Radar System (APAR).
[src:radar-systems/phased-array] The MIM-104 Patriot and other ground-based antiaircraft systems use phased array radar for similar benefits.
[src:radar-systems/phased-array] Phased arrays are used in naval sonar, in active (transmit and receive) and passive (receive only) and hull-mounted and towed array sonar.
[src:radar-systems/phased-array] One of first acoustic phased arrays was the German Gruppenhorchgerät device.
[src:radar-systems/phased-array] In acoustics, microphone arrays and line arrays of loudspeakers are also used.
[src:radar-systems/phased-array] The *MESSENGER* spacecraft was a space probe mission to the planet Mercury (2011–2015).
[src:radar-systems/phased-array] This was the first deep-space mission to use a phased-array antenna for communications.
[src:radar-systems/phased-array] The radiating elements are circularly-polarized, slotted waveguides.
[src:radar-systems/phased-array] The antenna, which uses the X band, used 26 radiative elements and can gracefully degrade.
[src:radar-systems/phased-array] The National Severe Storms Laboratory has been using a SPY-1A phased array antenna, provided by the US Navy, for weather research at its Norman, Oklahoma facility since April 23, 2003.
[src:radar-systems/phased-array] It is hoped that research will lead to a better understanding of thunderstorms and tornadoes, eventually leading to increased warning times and enhanced prediction of tornadoes.
[src:radar-systems/phased-array] The project includes research and development, future technology transfer and potential deployment of the system throughout the United States.
[src:radar-systems/phased-array] It is expected to take 10 to 15 years to complete and initial construction was approximately $25 million.
[src:radar-systems/phased-array] A team from Japan's RIKEN Advanced Institute for Computational Science (AICS) has begun experimental work on using phased-array radar with a new algorithm for instant weather forecasts.
[src:radar-systems/phased-array] Within the visible and infrared spectrum of electromagnetic waves it is possible to construct optical phased arrays (OPAs) which allow for dynamic beam forming and beam steering without mechanically moving parts.
[src:radar-systems/phased-array] They are used in wavelength multiplexers and filters for telecommunication purposes, as well as in Lidar, Free-space optical communication, and holography.
[src:radar-systems/phased-array] OPAs were also shown to enable lensless projectors, lensless cameras, and chip-scale optical tweezers.
[src:radar-systems/phased-array] Due to the short wavelengths OPAs are typically realised in nanofabricated photonic integrated circuit platforms utilising materials such as silicon on insulator, germanium on silicon, silicon nitride or polymers.
[src:radar-systems/phased-array] Synthetic array heterodyne detection is an efficient method for multiplexing an entire phased array onto a single element photodetector.
[src:radar-systems/phased-array] Starlink is a low Earth orbit satellite constellation that is available in over a hundred countries.
[src:radar-systems/phased-array] It provides broadband internet connectivity to consumers; the user terminals of the system use phased array antennas.
[src:radar-systems/phased-array] By 2014, phased array antennas were integrated into RFID systems to increase the area of coverage of a single system by 100% to 76,200 m2 (820,000 sq ft) while still using traditional passive UHF tags.
[src:radar-systems/phased-array] A phased array of acoustic transducers, denominated airborne ultrasound tactile display (AUTD), was developed in 2008 at the University of Tokyo's Shinoda Lab to induce tactile feedback.
[src:radar-systems/phased-array] This system was demonstrated to enable a user to interactively manipulate virtual holographic objects.
[src:radar-systems/phased-array] Phased Array Feeds (PAF) have recently been used at the focus of radio telescopes to provide many beams, giving the radio telescope a very wide field of view.
[src:radar-systems/phased-array] Three examples are the ASKAP telescope in Australia, the Apertif upgrade to the Westerbork Synthesis Radio Telescope in the Netherlands, and the Florida Space Institute in the United States .
[src:radar-systems/phased-array] In broadcast engineering, the term 'phased array' has a meaning different from its normal meaning, it means an ordinary array antenna, an array of multiple mast radiators designed to radiate a directional radiation pattern, as opposed to a single mast which radiates an omnidirectional pattern.
[src:radar-systems/phased-array] Broadcast phased arrays have fixed radiation patterns and are not 'steered' during operation as are other phased arrays.
[src:radar-systems/phased-array] Phased arrays are used by many AM broadcast radio stations to enhance signal strength and therefore coverage in the city of license, while minimizing interference to other areas.
[src:radar-systems/phased-array] For shortwave broadcasts many stations use arrays of horizontal dipoles.
[src:radar-systems/phased-array] A common arrangement uses 16 dipoles in a 4×4 array.
[src:radar-systems/phased-array] Usually this is in front of a wire grid reflector.
[src:radar-systems/phased-array] The phasing is often switchable to allow beam steering in azimuth and sometimes elevation.
[src:radar-systems/pulse-doppler-radar] A **pulse-Doppler radar** is a radar system that determines the range to a target using pulse-timing techniques, and uses the Doppler effect of the returned signal to determine the target object's velocity.
[src:radar-systems/pulse-doppler-radar] It combines the features of pulse radars and continuous-wave radars, which were formerly separate due to the complexity of the electronics.
[src:radar-systems/pulse-doppler-radar] The first operational pulse-Doppler radar was in the CIM-10 Bomarc, an American long-range supersonic missile powered by ramjet engines, and which was armed with a W40 nuclear weapon to destroy entire formations of attacking enemy aircraft.
[src:radar-systems/pulse-doppler-radar] Pulse-Doppler systems were first widely used on fighter aircraft starting in the 1960s.
[src:radar-systems/pulse-doppler-radar] Earlier radars had used pulse-timing in order to determine range and the angle of the antenna (or similar means) to determine the bearing.
[src:radar-systems/pulse-doppler-radar] However, this only worked when the radar antenna was not pointed down; in that case the reflection off the ground overwhelmed any returns from other objects.
[src:radar-systems/pulse-doppler-radar] As the ground moves at the same speed but opposite direction of the aircraft, Doppler techniques allow the ground return to be filtered out, revealing aircraft and vehicles.
[src:radar-systems/pulse-doppler-radar] This gives pulse-Doppler radars "look-down/shoot-down" capability.
[src:radar-systems/pulse-doppler-radar] A secondary advantage in military radar is to reduce the transmitted power while achieving acceptable performance for improved safety of stealthy radar.
[src:radar-systems/pulse-doppler-radar] Pulse-Doppler techniques also find widespread use in meteorological radars, allowing the radar to determine wind speed from the velocity of any precipitation in the air.
[src:radar-systems/pulse-doppler-radar] Pulse-Doppler radar is also the basis of synthetic aperture radar used in radar astronomy, remote sensing and mapping.
[src:radar-systems/pulse-doppler-radar] In air traffic control, they are used for discriminating aircraft from clutter.
[src:radar-systems/pulse-doppler-radar] Besides the above conventional surveillance applications, pulse-Doppler radar has been successfully applied in healthcare, such as fall risk assessment and fall detection, for nursing or clinical purposes.
[src:radar-systems/pulse-doppler-radar] The earliest radar systems failed to operate as expected.
[src:radar-systems/pulse-doppler-radar] The reason was traced to Doppler effects that degrade performance of systems not designed to account for moving objects.
[src:radar-systems/pulse-doppler-radar] Fast-moving objects cause a phase-shift on the transmit pulse that can produce signal cancellation.
[src:radar-systems/pulse-doppler-radar] Doppler has maximum detrimental effect on moving target indicator systems, which must use reverse phase shift for Doppler compensation in the detector.
[src:radar-systems/pulse-doppler-radar] Doppler weather effects (precipitation) were also found to degrade conventional radar and moving target indicator radar, which can mask aircraft reflections.
[src:radar-systems/pulse-doppler-radar] This phenomenon was adapted for use with weather radar in the 1950s after declassification of some World War II systems.
[src:radar-systems/pulse-doppler-radar] Pulse-Doppler radar was developed during World War II to overcome limitations by increasing pulse repetition frequency.
[src:radar-systems/pulse-doppler-radar] This required the development of the klystron, the traveling wave tube, and solid state devices.
[src:radar-systems/pulse-doppler-radar] Early pulse-dopplers were incompatible with other high power microwave amplification devices that are not coherent, but more sophisticated techniques were developed that record the phase of each transmitted pulse for comparison to returned echoes.
[src:radar-systems/pulse-doppler-radar] Early examples of military systems includes the AN/SPG-51B developed during the 1950s specifically for the purpose of operating in hurricane conditions with no performance degradation.
[src:radar-systems/pulse-doppler-radar] The Hughes AN/ASG-18 Fire Control System was a prototype airborne radar/combination system for the planned North American XF-108 Rapier interceptor aircraft for the United States Air Force, and later for the Lockheed YF-12.
[src:radar-systems/pulse-doppler-radar] The US's first pulse-Doppler radar, the system had look-down/shoot-down capability and could track one target at a time.
[src:radar-systems/pulse-doppler-radar] It became possible to use pulse-Doppler radar on aircraft after digital computers were incorporated in the design.
[src:radar-systems/pulse-doppler-radar] Pulse-Doppler provided look-down/shoot-down capability to support air-to-air missile systems in most modern military aircraft by the mid 1970s.
[src:radar-systems/pulse-doppler-radar] Pulse-Doppler systems measure the range to objects by measuring the elapsed time between sending a pulse of radio energy and receiving a reflection of the object.
[src:radar-systems/pulse-doppler-radar] Radio waves travel at the speed of light, so the distance to the object is the elapsed time multiplied by the speed of light, divided by two – there and back.
[src:radar-systems/pulse-doppler-radar] Radial velocity is essential for pulse-Doppler radar operation.
[src:radar-systems/pulse-doppler-radar] As the reflector moves between each transmit pulse, the returned signal has a phase difference, or *phase shift*, from pulse to pulse.
[src:radar-systems/pulse-doppler-radar] This causes the reflector to produce Doppler modulation on the reflected signal.
[src:radar-systems/pulse-doppler-radar] Pulse-Doppler radars exploit this phenomenon to improve performance.
[src:radar-systems/pulse-doppler-radar] Rejection speed is selectable on pulse-Doppler aircraft-detection systems so nothing below that speed will be detected.
[src:radar-systems/pulse-doppler-radar] A one degree antenna beam illuminates millions of square feet of terrain at 10 miles (16 km) range, and this produces thousands of detections at or below the horizon if Doppler is not used.
[src:radar-systems/pulse-doppler-radar] Pulse-Doppler radar uses the following signal processing criteria to exclude unwanted signals from slow-moving objects.
[src:radar-systems/pulse-doppler-radar] This is also known as clutter rejection.
[src:radar-systems/pulse-doppler-radar] Rejection velocity is usually set just above the prevailing wind speed (10 to 100 mph or 20 to 160 km/h).
[src:radar-systems/pulse-doppler-radar] Surface reflections appear in almost all radar.
[src:radar-systems/pulse-doppler-radar] **Ground clutter** generally appears in a circular region within a radius of about 25 miles (40 km) near ground-based radar.
[src:radar-systems/pulse-doppler-radar] This distance extends much further in airborne and space radar.
[src:radar-systems/pulse-doppler-radar] Clutter results from radio energy being reflected from the earth surface, buildings, and vegetation.
[src:radar-systems/pulse-doppler-radar] Clutter includes weather in radar intended to detect and report aircraft and spacecraft.
[src:radar-systems/pulse-doppler-radar] Clutter creates a vulnerability region in pulse-amplitude time-domain radar.
[src:radar-systems/pulse-doppler-radar] Non-Doppler radar systems cannot be pointed directly at the ground due to excessive false alarms, which overwhelm computers and operators.
[src:radar-systems/pulse-doppler-radar] Sensitivity must be reduced near clutter to avoid overload.
[src:radar-systems/pulse-doppler-radar] This vulnerability begins in the low-elevation region several beam widths above the horizon, and extends downward.
[src:radar-systems/pulse-doppler-radar] This also exists throughout the volume of moving air associated with weather phenomenon.
[src:radar-systems/pulse-doppler-radar] Pulse-Doppler radar corrects this as follows.
[src:radar-systems/pulse-doppler-radar] Clutter rejection capability of about 60 dB is needed for look-down/shoot-down capability, and pulse-Doppler is the only strategy that can satisfy this requirement.
[src:radar-systems/pulse-doppler-radar] This eliminates vulnerabilities associated with the low-elevation and below-horizon environment.
[src:radar-systems/pulse-doppler-radar] Pulse compression and moving target indicator (MTI) provide up to 25 dB sub-clutter visibility.
[src:radar-systems/pulse-doppler-radar] An MTI antenna beam is aimed above the horizon to avoid an excessive false alarm rate, which renders systems vulnerable.
[src:radar-systems/pulse-doppler-radar] Aircraft and some missiles exploit this weakness using a technique called **flying below the radar** to avoid detection (nap-of-the-earth).
[src:radar-systems/pulse-doppler-radar] This flying technique is ineffective against pulse-Doppler radar.
[src:radar-systems/pulse-doppler-radar] Pulse-Doppler provides an advantage when attempting to detect missiles and low observability aircraft flying near terrain, sea surface, and weather.
[src:radar-systems/pulse-doppler-radar] Audible Doppler and target size support passive vehicle type classification when identification friend or foe is not available from a transponder signal.
[src:radar-systems/pulse-doppler-radar] Medium pulse repetition frequency (PRF) reflected microwave signals fall between 1,500 and 15,000 cycle per second, which is audible.
[src:radar-systems/pulse-doppler-radar] This means a helicopter sounds like a helicopter, a jet sounds like a jet, and propeller aircraft sound like propellers.
[src:radar-systems/pulse-doppler-radar] Aircraft with no moving parts produce a tone.
[src:radar-systems/pulse-doppler-radar] The actual size of the target can be calculated using the audible signal.
[src:radar-systems/pulse-doppler-radar] Ambiguity processing is required when target range is above the red line in the graphic, which increases scan time.
[src:radar-systems/pulse-doppler-radar] Scan time is a critical factor for some systems because vehicles moving at or above the speed of sound can travel one mile (1.6 km) every few seconds, like the Exocet, Harpoon, Kitchen, and air-to-air missiles.
[src:radar-systems/pulse-doppler-radar] The maximum time to scan the entire volume of the sky must be on the order of a dozen seconds or less for systems operating in that environment.
[src:radar-systems/pulse-doppler-radar] Pulse-Doppler radar by itself can be too slow to cover the entire volume of space above the horizon unless fan beam is used.
[src:radar-systems/pulse-doppler-radar] This approach is used with the AN/SPS 49(V)5 Very Long Range Air Surveillance Radar, which sacrifices elevation measurement to gain speed.
[src:radar-systems/pulse-doppler-radar] Pulse-Doppler antenna motion must be slow enough so that all the return signals from at least 3 different PRFs can be processed out to the maximum anticipated detection range.
[src:radar-systems/pulse-doppler-radar] Antenna motion for pulse-Doppler must be as slow as radar using MTI.
[src:radar-systems/pulse-doppler-radar] The antenna type is an important consideration for multi-mode radar because undesirable phase shift introduced by the radar antenna can degrade performance measurements for sub-clutter visibility.
[src:radar-systems/pulse-doppler-radar] The signal processing enhancement of pulse-Doppler allows small high-speed objects to be detected in close proximity to large slow moving reflectors.
[src:radar-systems/pulse-doppler-radar] To achieve this, the transmitter must be coherent and should produce low phase noise during the detection interval, and the receiver must have large instantaneous dynamic range.
[src:radar-systems/pulse-doppler-radar] Pulse-Doppler signal processing also includes ambiguity resolution to identify true range and velocity.
[src:radar-systems/pulse-doppler-radar] The received signals from multiple PRF are compared to determine true range using the range ambiguity resolution process.
[src:radar-systems/pulse-doppler-radar] The received signals are also compared using the frequency ambiguity resolution process.
[src:radar-systems/pulse-doppler-radar] In addition to this sampling limit, the duration of the transmitted pulse could mean that returns from two targets will be received simultaneously from different parts of the pulse.
[src:radar-systems/pulse-doppler-radar] Pulse-Doppler radar has special requirements that must be satisfied to achieve acceptable performance.
[src:radar-systems/pulse-doppler-radar] Pulse-Doppler typically uses medium pulse repetition frequency (PRF) from about 3 kHz to 30 kHz.
[src:radar-systems/pulse-doppler-radar] The range between transmit pulses is 5 km to 50 km.
[src:radar-systems/pulse-doppler-radar] Range and velocity cannot be measured directly using medium PRF, and ambiguity resolution is required to identify true range and speed.
[src:radar-systems/pulse-doppler-radar] Doppler signals are generally above 1 kHz, which is audible, so audio signals from medium-PRF systems can be used for passive target classification.
[src:radar-systems/pulse-doppler-radar] Radar systems require angular measurement.
[src:radar-systems/pulse-doppler-radar] Transponders are not normally associated with pulse-Doppler radar, so sidelobe suppression is required for practical operation.
[src:radar-systems/pulse-doppler-radar] Tracking radar systems use angle error to improve accuracy by producing measurements perpendicular to the radar antenna beam.
[src:radar-systems/pulse-doppler-radar] Angular measurements are averaged over a span of time and combined with radial movement to develop information suitable to predict target position for a short time into the future.
[src:radar-systems/pulse-doppler-radar] The two angle error techniques used with tracking radar are monopulse and conical scan.
[src:radar-systems/pulse-doppler-radar] Pulse-Doppler radar requires a coherent oscillator with very little noise.
[src:radar-systems/pulse-doppler-radar] Phase noise reduces sub-clutter visibility performance by producing apparent motion on stationary objects.
[src:radar-systems/pulse-doppler-radar] Cavity magnetron and crossed-field amplifier are not appropriate because noise introduced by these devices interfere with detection performance.
[src:radar-systems/pulse-doppler-radar] The only amplification devices suitable for pulse-Doppler are klystron, traveling wave tube, and solid state devices.
[src:radar-systems/pulse-doppler-radar] Pulse-Doppler signal processing introduces a phenomenon called scalloping.
[src:radar-systems/pulse-doppler-radar] The name is associated with a series of holes that are scooped-out of the detection performance.
[src:radar-systems/pulse-doppler-radar] Scalloping for pulse-Doppler radar involves blind velocities created by the clutter rejection filter.
[src:radar-systems/pulse-doppler-radar] Every volume of space must be scanned using 3 or more different PRF.
[src:radar-systems/pulse-doppler-radar] A two PRF detection scheme will have **detection gaps** with a pattern of discrete ranges, each of which has a blind velocity.
[src:radar-systems/pulse-doppler-radar] Ringing artifacts pose a problem with search, detection, and ambiguity resolution in pulse-Doppler radar.
[src:radar-systems/pulse-doppler-radar] First, the shape of the transmit pulse is adjusted to smooth the leading edge and trailing edge so that RF power is increased and decreased without an abrupt change.
[src:radar-systems/pulse-doppler-radar] This creates a transmit pulse with smooth ends instead of a square wave, which reduces ringing phenomenon that is otherwise associated with target reflection.
[src:radar-systems/pulse-doppler-radar] Second, the shape of the receive pulse is adjusted using a window function that minimizes ringing that occurs any time pulses are applied to a filter.
[src:radar-systems/pulse-doppler-radar] In a digital system, this adjusts the phase and/or amplitude of each sample before it is applied to the fast Fourier transform.
[src:radar-systems/pulse-doppler-radar] The Dolph-Chebyshev window is the most effective because it produces a flat processing floor with no ringing that would otherwise cause false alarms.
[src:radar-systems/pulse-doppler-radar] Pulse-Doppler radar is generally limited to mechanically aimed antennas and active phased arrays.
[src:radar-systems/pulse-doppler-radar] Mechanical RF components, such as wave-guide, can produce Doppler modulation due to phase shift induced by vibration.
[src:radar-systems/pulse-doppler-radar] This introduces a requirement to perform full spectrum operational tests using shake tables that can produce high power mechanical vibration across all anticipated audio frequencies.
[src:radar-systems/pulse-doppler-radar] Doppler is incompatible with most passive electronically steered phased-array antenna.
[src:radar-systems/pulse-doppler-radar] This is because the phase-shifter elements in the antenna are non-reciprocal and the phase shift must be adjusted before and after each transmit pulse.
[src:radar-systems/pulse-doppler-radar] Spurious phase shift is produced by the sudden impulse of the phase shift, and settling during the receive period between transmit pulses places Doppler modulation onto stationary clutter.
[src:radar-systems/pulse-doppler-radar] That receive modulation corrupts the measure of performance for sub-clutter visibility.
[src:radar-systems/pulse-doppler-radar] Phase shifter settling time on the order of 50ns is required.
[src:radar-systems/pulse-doppler-radar] Start of receiver sampling needs to be postponed at least 1 phase-shifter settling time-constant (or more) for each 20 dB of sub-clutter visibility.
[src:radar-systems/pulse-doppler-radar] Most antenna phase shifters operating at PRF above 1 kHz introduce spurious phase shift unless special provisions are made, such as reducing phase shifter settling time to a few dozen nanoseconds.
[src:radar-systems/pulse-doppler-radar] The antenna type and scan performance is a practical consideration for multi-mode radar systems.
[src:radar-systems/pulse-doppler-radar] Choppy surfaces, like waves and trees, form a diffraction grating suitable for bending microwave signals.
[src:radar-systems/pulse-doppler-radar] Pulse-Doppler can be so sensitive that diffraction from mountains, buildings or wave tops can be used to detect fast moving objects otherwise blocked by solid obstruction along the line of sight.
[src:radar-systems/pulse-doppler-radar] This is a very lossy phenomenon that only becomes possible when radar has significant excess sub-clutter visibility.
[src:radar-systems/pulse-doppler-radar] Refraction and ducting use transmit frequency at L-band or lower to extend the horizon, which is very different from diffraction.
[src:radar-systems/pulse-doppler-radar] Refraction for over-the-horizon radar uses variable density in the air column above the surface of the earth to bend RF signals.
[src:radar-systems/pulse-doppler-radar] An inversion layer can produce a transient troposphere duct that traps RF signals in a thin layer of air like a wave-guide.
[src:radar-systems/pulse-doppler-radar] Subclutter visibility involves the maximum ratio of clutter power to target power, which is proportional to dynamic range.
[src:radar-systems/pulse-doppler-radar] The pulse-Doppler radar equation can be used to understand trade-offs between different design constraints, like power consumption, detection range, and microwave safety hazards.
[src:radar-systems/pulse-doppler-radar] This is a very simple form of modeling that allows performance to be evaluated in a sterile environment.
[src:radar-systems/pulse-doppler-radar] The theoretical range performance is as follows.
[src:radar-systems/pulse-doppler-radar] This equation is derived by combining the radar equation with the noise equation and accounting for in-band noise distribution across multiple detection filters.
[src:radar-systems/pulse-doppler-radar] The value *D* is added to the standard radar range equation to account for both pulse-Doppler signal processing and transmitter FM noise reduction.
[src:radar-systems/pulse-doppler-radar] Detection range is increased proportional to the fourth root of the number of filters for a given power consumption.
[src:radar-systems/pulse-doppler-radar] Alternatively, power consumption is reduced by the number of filters for a given detection range.
[src:radar-systems/pulse-doppler-radar] Pulse-Doppler signal processing integrates all of the energy from all of the individual reflected pulses that enter the filter.
[src:radar-systems/pulse-doppler-radar] This means a pulse-Doppler signal processing system with 1024 elements provides 30.103 dB of improvement due to the type of signal processing that must be used with pulse-Doppler radar.
[src:radar-systems/pulse-doppler-radar] The energy of all of the individual pulses from the object are added together by the filtering process.
[src:radar-systems/pulse-doppler-radar] Signal processing for a 1024-point filter improves performance by 30.103 dB, assuming compatible transmitter and antenna.
[src:radar-systems/pulse-doppler-radar] This corresponds to 562% increase in maximal distance.
[src:radar-systems/pulse-doppler-radar] These improvements are the reason pulse-Doppler is essential for military and astronomy.
[src:radar-systems/pulse-doppler-radar] Pulse-Doppler radar for aircraft detection has two modes.
[src:radar-systems/pulse-doppler-radar] Scan mode involves frequency filtering, amplitude thresholding, and ambiguity resolution.
[src:radar-systems/pulse-doppler-radar] Once a reflection has been detected and resolved, the pulse-Doppler radar automatically transitions to tracking mode for the volume of space surrounding the track.
[src:radar-systems/pulse-doppler-radar] Track mode works like a phase-locked loop, where Doppler velocity is compared with the range movement on successive scans.
[src:radar-systems/pulse-doppler-radar] **Lock** indicates the difference between the two measurements is below a threshold, which can only occur with an object that satisfies Newtonian mechanics.
[src:radar-systems/pulse-doppler-radar] Other types of electronic signals cannot produce a lock.
[src:radar-systems/pulse-doppler-radar] The **lock criterion** needs to be satisfied during normal operation.
[src:radar-systems/pulse-doppler-radar] Lock eliminates the need for human intervention with the exception of helicopters and electronic jamming.
[src:radar-systems/pulse-doppler-radar] Weather phenomenon obey adiabatic process associated with air mass and not Newtonian mechanics, so the lock criterion is not normally used for weather radar.
[src:radar-systems/pulse-doppler-radar] Pulse-Doppler signal processing selectively excludes low-velocity reflections so that no detections occurs below a threshold velocity.
[src:radar-systems/pulse-doppler-radar] This eliminates terrain, weather, biologicals, and mechanical jamming with the exception of decoy aircraft.
[src:radar-systems/pulse-doppler-radar] The target Doppler signal from the detection is converted from frequency domain back into time domain sound for the operator in track mode on some radar systems.
[src:radar-systems/pulse-doppler-radar] The operator uses this sound for passive target classification, such as recognizing helicopters and electronic jamming.
[src:radar-systems/pulse-doppler-radar] Special consideration is required for aircraft with large moving parts because pulse-Doppler radar operates like a phase-locked loop.
[src:radar-systems/pulse-doppler-radar] Blade tips moving near the speed of sound produce the only signal that can be detected when a helicopter is moving slow near terrain and weather.
[src:radar-systems/pulse-doppler-radar] A helicopter appears like a rapidly pulsing noise emitter except in a clear environment free from clutter.
[src:radar-systems/pulse-doppler-radar] An audible signal is produced for passive identification of the type of airborne object.
[src:radar-systems/pulse-doppler-radar] Microwave Doppler frequency shift produced by reflector motion falls into the audible sound range for human beings (20–20000 Hz), which is used for target classification in addition to the kinds of conventional radar display used for that purpose, like A-scope, B-scope, C-scope, and RHI indicator.
[src:radar-systems/pulse-doppler-radar] The human ear may be able to tell the difference better than electronic equipment.
[src:radar-systems/pulse-doppler-radar] A special mode is required because the Doppler velocity feedback information must be unlinked from radial movement so that the system can transition from scan to track with no lock.
[src:radar-systems/pulse-doppler-radar] Similar techniques are required to develop track information for jamming signals and interference that cannot satisfy the lock criterion.
[src:radar-systems/pulse-doppler-radar] Pulse-Doppler radar must be multi-mode to handle aircraft turning and crossing trajectory.
[src:radar-systems/pulse-doppler-radar] Once in track mode, pulse-Doppler radar must include a way to modify Doppler filtering for the volume of space surrounding a track when radial velocity falls below the minimum detection velocity.
[src:radar-systems/pulse-doppler-radar] Doppler filter adjustment must be linked with a radar track function to automatically adjust Doppler rejection speed within the volume of space surrounding the track.
[src:radar-systems/pulse-doppler-radar] Tracking will cease without this feature because the target signal will otherwise be rejected by the Doppler filter when radial velocity approaches zero because there is no change in frequency.
[src:radar-systems/pulse-doppler-radar] Multi-mode operation may also include continuous wave illumination for semi-active radar homing.
[src:radar-systems/radar-cross-section] An object reflects a limited amount of radar energy back to the source.
[src:radar-systems/radar-cross-section] While important in detecting targets, strength of emitter and distance are not factors that affect the calculation of an RCS because RCS is a property of the target's reflectivity.
[src:radar-systems/radar-cross-section] Radar cross section is used to detect airplanes in a wide variation of ranges.
[src:radar-systems/radar-cross-section] RCS is integral to the development of radar stealth technology, particularly in applications involving aircraft and ballistic missiles.
[src:radar-systems/radar-cross-section] RCS data for current military aircraft is mostly highly classified.
[src:radar-systems/radar-cross-section] In some cases, it is of interest to look at an area on the ground that includes many objects.
[src:radar-systems/radar-cross-section] The NRCS has units of area per area, or ⁠m2/m2⁠ in MKS units.
[src:radar-systems/radar-cross-section] Informally, the RCS of an object is the cross-sectional area of a perfectly reflecting sphere that would produce the same strength reflection as would the object in question.
[src:radar-systems/radar-cross-section] (Bigger sizes of this imaginary sphere would produce stronger reflections.) Thus, RCS is an abstraction: the radar cross-sectional area of an object does not necessarily bear a direct relationship with the physical cross-sectional area of that object but depends upon other factors.
[src:radar-systems/radar-cross-section] Somewhat less informally, the RCS of a radar target is an effective area that intercepts the transmitted radar power and then scatters that power isotropically back to the radar receiver.
[src:radar-systems/radar-cross-section] More precisely, the RCS of a radar target is the hypothetical area required to intercept the transmitted power density at the target such that if the total intercepted power were re-radiated isotropically, the power density actually observed at the receiver is produced.
[src:radar-systems/radar-cross-section] The ${\textstyle {{P_{t}G_{t}} \over {4\pi r^{2}}}}$ term in the radar equation represents the power density (watts per meter squared) that the radar transmitter produces at the target.
[src:radar-systems/radar-cross-section] This power density is intercepted by the target with radar cross section ${\textstyle \sigma }$ , which has units of area (meters squared).
[src:radar-systems/radar-cross-section] Thus, the product ${\textstyle {{P_{t}G_{t}} \over {4\pi r^{2}}}\sigma }$ has the dimensions of power (watts), and represents a hypothetical total power intercepted by the radar target.
[src:radar-systems/radar-cross-section] The second ${\textstyle {{1} \over {4\pi r^{2}}}}$ term represents isotropic spreading of this intercepted power from the target back to the radar receiver.
[src:radar-systems/radar-cross-section] Thus, the product ${\textstyle {{P_{t}G_{t}} \over {4\pi r^{2}}}\sigma {{1} \over {4\pi r^{2}}}}$ represents the reflected power density at the radar receiver (again watts per meter squared).
[src:radar-systems/radar-cross-section] The receiver antenna then collects this power density with effective area ${\textstyle A_{\mathrm {eff} }}$ , yielding the power received by the radar (watts) as given by the radar equation above.
[src:radar-systems/radar-cross-section] The scattering of incident radar power by a radar target is never isotropic (even for a spherical target), and the RCS is a hypothetical area.
[src:radar-systems/radar-cross-section] In this light, RCS can be viewed as a correction factor that makes the radar equation "work out right" for the experimentally observed ratio of ${\textstyle P_{r}/P_{t}}$ .
[src:radar-systems/radar-cross-section] However, RCS is a property of the target alone and may be measured or calculated.
[src:radar-systems/radar-cross-section] Thus, RCS allows the performance of a radar system with a given target to be analysed independent of the radar and engagement parameters.
[src:radar-systems/radar-cross-section] In general, RCS is a function of the orientation of the radar and target.
[src:radar-systems/radar-cross-section] A target's RCS depends on its size, *reflectivity* of its surface, and the *directivity* of the radar return caused by the target's geometric shape.
[src:radar-systems/radar-cross-section] As a rule, the larger an object, the stronger its radar reflection and thus the greater its RCS.
[src:radar-systems/radar-cross-section] Also, radar of one band may not even detect certain size objects.
[src:radar-systems/radar-cross-section] For example, 10 cm (S-band radar) can detect rain drops but not clouds whose droplets are too small.
[src:radar-systems/radar-cross-section] Materials such as metal are strongly radar reflective and tend to produce strong signals.
[src:radar-systems/radar-cross-section] Wood and cloth (such as portions of airplanes and balloons used to be commonly made) or plastic and fibreglass are less reflective or indeed transparent to radar making them suitable for radomes.
[src:radar-systems/radar-cross-section] Even a very thin layer of metal can make an object strongly radar reflective.
[src:radar-systems/radar-cross-section] Chaff is often made from metallised plastic or glass (in a similar manner to metallised foils on food stuffs) with microscopically thin layers of metal.
[src:radar-systems/radar-cross-section] Also, some devices are designed to be Radar active, such as radar antennas and this will increase RCS.
[src:radar-systems/radar-cross-section] The SR-71 Blackbird and other aircraft were painted with a special "iron ball paint" that consisted of small metallic-coated balls.
[src:radar-systems/radar-cross-section] Radar energy received is converted to heat rather than being reflected.
[src:radar-systems/radar-cross-section] The surfaces of the F-117A are designed to be flat and very angled.
[src:radar-systems/radar-cross-section] This has the effect that radar will be incident at a large angle (to the normal ray) that will then bounce off at a similarly high reflected angle; it is forward-scattered.
[src:radar-systems/radar-cross-section] The edges are sharp to prevent rounded surfaces which are normal at some point to the radar source.
[src:radar-systems/radar-cross-section] As any ray incident along the normal will reflect back along the normal, rounded surfaces make for a strong reflected signal.
[src:radar-systems/radar-cross-section] From the side, a fighter aircraft will present a much larger area than the same aircraft viewed from the front.
[src:radar-systems/radar-cross-section] All other factors being equal, the aircraft will have a stronger signal from the side than from the front; hence the orientation of the target relative to the radar station is important.
[src:radar-systems/radar-cross-section] The relief of a surface could contain indentations that act as corner reflectors which would increase RCS from many orientations.
[src:radar-systems/radar-cross-section] This could arise from open bomb-bays, engine intakes, ordnance pylons, joints between constructed sections, etc.
[src:radar-systems/radar-cross-section] Also, it can be impractical to coat these surfaces with radar-absorbent materials.
[src:radar-systems/radar-cross-section] The size of a target's image on radar is measured by the radar cross section or RCS, often represented by the symbol σ and expressed in square meters.
[src:radar-systems/radar-cross-section] A perfectly conducting sphere of projected cross sectional area 1 m2 (i.e. a diameter of 1.13 m) will have an RCS of 1 m2.
[src:radar-systems/radar-cross-section] For radar wavelengths much less than the diameter of the sphere, RCS is independent of frequency.
[src:radar-systems/radar-cross-section] Conversely, a square flat plate of area 1 m2 will have an RCS of σ = 4π *A*2 / *λ*2 (where *A*=area, *λ*=wavelength), or 139.62 m2 at 1 GHz if the radar is perpendicular to the flat surface.
[src:radar-systems/radar-cross-section] At off-normal incident angles, energy is reflected away from the receiver, reducing the RCS.
[src:radar-systems/radar-cross-section] Modern stealth aircraft are said to have an RCS comparable with small birds or large insects, though this varies widely depending on aircraft and radar.
[src:radar-systems/radar-cross-section] If the RCS was directly related to the target's cross-sectional area, the only way to reduce it would be to make the physical profile smaller.
[src:radar-systems/radar-cross-section] Rather, by reflecting much of the radiation away or by absorbing it, the target achieves a smaller radar cross section.
[src:radar-systems/radar-cross-section] Measurement of a target's RCS is performed at a radar reflectivity range or scattering range.
[src:radar-systems/radar-cross-section] The first type of range is an outdoor range where the target is positioned on a specially shaped low RCS pylon some distance down-range from the transmitters.
[src:radar-systems/radar-cross-section] Such a range eliminates the need for placing radar absorbers behind the target, however multi-path interactions with the ground must be mitigated.
[src:radar-systems/radar-cross-section] An anechoic chamber is also commonly used.
[src:radar-systems/radar-cross-section] In such a room, the target is placed on a rotating pillar in the center, and the walls, floors and ceiling are covered by stacks of radar absorbing material.
[src:radar-systems/radar-cross-section] These absorbers prevent corruption of the measurement due to reflections.
[src:radar-systems/radar-cross-section] A compact range is an anechoic chamber with a reflector to simulate far field conditions.
[src:radar-systems/radar-cross-section] Where $\sigma$ is the RCS, $S_{i}$ is the incident power density measured at the target, and $S_{s}$ is the scattered power density seen at a distance r away from the target.
[src:radar-systems/radar-cross-section] where $E_{s}$ and $E_{i}$ are the far field scattered and incident electric field intensities, respectively.
[src:radar-systems/radar-cross-section] In the design phase, it is often desirable to employ a computer to predict what the RCS will look like before fabricating an actual object.
[src:radar-systems/radar-cross-section] Many iterations of this prediction process can be performed in a short time at low cost, whereas use of a measurement range is often time-consuming, expensive and error-prone.
[src:radar-systems/radar-cross-section] The linearity of Maxwell's equations makes RCS relatively straightforward to calculate with a variety of analytic and numerical methods, but changing levels of military interest and the need for secrecy have made the field challenging, nonetheless.
[src:radar-systems/radar-cross-section] The field of solving Maxwell's equations through numerical algorithms is called computational electromagnetics, and many effective analysis methods have been applied to the RCS prediction problem.
[src:radar-systems/radar-cross-section] RCS prediction software are often run on large supercomputers and employ high-resolution CAD models of real radar targets.
[src:radar-systems/radar-cross-section] High frequency approximations such as geometric optics, physical optics, the geometric theory of diffraction, the uniform theory of diffraction and the physical theory of diffraction are used when the wavelength is much shorter than the target feature size.
[src:radar-systems/radar-cross-section] Statistical models include chi-square, Rice, and the log-normal target models.
[src:radar-systems/radar-cross-section] These models are used to predict likely values of the RCS given an average value, and are useful when running radar Monte Carlo simulations.
[src:radar-systems/radar-cross-section] Purely numerical methods such as the boundary element method (method of moments), finite difference time domain method (FDTD) and finite element methods are limited by computer performance to longer wavelengths or smaller features.
[src:radar-systems/radar-cross-section] Though, for simple cases, the wavelength ranges of these two types of method overlap considerably, for difficult shapes and materials or very high accuracy they are combined in various sorts of hybrid method.
[src:radar-systems/radar-cross-section] RCS reduction is chiefly important in stealth technology for aircraft, missiles, ships, and other military vehicles.
[src:radar-systems/radar-cross-section] With smaller RCS, vehicles can better evade radar detection, whether it be from land-based installations, guided weapons or other vehicles.
[src:radar-systems/radar-cross-section] Reduced signature design also improves platforms' overall survivability through the improved effectiveness of its radar counter-measures.
[src:radar-systems/radar-cross-section] The distance at which a target can be detected for a given radar configuration varies with the fourth root of its RCS.
[src:radar-systems/radar-cross-section] Therefore, in order to cut the detection distance to one tenth, the RCS should be reduced by a factor of 10,000.
[src:radar-systems/radar-cross-section] While this degree of improvement is challenging, it is often possible when influencing platforms during the concept/design stage and using experts and advanced computer code simulations to implement the control options described below.
[src:radar-systems/radar-cross-section] With purpose shaping, the shape of the target's reflecting surfaces is designed such that they reflect energy away from the source.
[src:radar-systems/radar-cross-section] The aim is usually to create a "cone-of-silence" about the target's direction of motion.
[src:radar-systems/radar-cross-section] Due to the energy reflection, this method is defeated by using passive (multistatic) radars.
[src:radar-systems/radar-cross-section] Purpose-shaping can be seen in the design of surface faceting on the F-117A Nighthawk stealth attack aircraft.
[src:radar-systems/radar-cross-section] This aircraft, designed in the late 1970s though only revealed to the public in 1988, uses a multitude of flat surfaces to reflect incident radar energy away from the source.
[src:radar-systems/radar-cross-section] Yue suggests that limited available computing power for the design phase kept the number of surfaces to a minimum.
[src:radar-systems/radar-cross-section] The B-2 Spirit stealth bomber benefited from increased computing power, enabling its contoured shapes and further reduction in RCS.
[src:radar-systems/radar-cross-section] The F-22 Raptor and F-35 Lightning II continue the trend in purpose shaping and promise to have even smaller monostatic RCS.
[src:radar-systems/radar-cross-section] This technique is relatively new compared to other techniques chiefly after the invention of metasurfaces.
[src:radar-systems/radar-cross-section] As mentioned earlier, the primary objective in geometry alteration is to redirect scattered waves away from the backscattered direction (or the source).
[src:radar-systems/radar-cross-section] However, it may compromise performance in terms of aerodynamics.
[src:radar-systems/radar-cross-section] One feasible solution, which has extensively been explored in recent time, is to utilize metasurfaces which can redirect scattered waves without altering the geometry of the target.
[src:radar-systems/radar-cross-section] Such metasurfaces can primarily be classified in two categories: (i) Checkerboard metasurfaces, (ii) Gradient index metasurfaces.
[src:radar-systems/radar-cross-section] With active cancellation, the target generates a radar signal equal in intensity but opposite in phase to the predicted reflection of an incident radar signal (similarly to noise canceling ear phones).
[src:radar-systems/radar-cross-section] This creates destructive interference between the reflected and generated signals, resulting in reduced RCS.
[src:radar-systems/radar-cross-section] To incorporate active cancellation techniques, the precise characteristics of the waveform and angle of arrival of the illuminating radar signal must be known, since they define the nature of generated energy required for cancellation.
[src:radar-systems/radar-cross-section] Radar absorbent material (RAM) can be used in the original construction, or as an addition to highly reflective surfaces.
[src:radar-systems/radar-cross-section] There are at least three types of RAM: resonant, non-resonant magnetic and non-resonant large volume.
[src:radar-systems/radar-cross-section] Thin coatings made of only dielectrics and conductors have very limited absorbing bandwidth, so magnetic materials are used when weight and cost permit, either in resonant RAM or as non-resonant RAM.
[src:radar-systems/radar-cross-section] Thin non-resonant or broad resonance coatings can be modeled with a Leontovich impedance boundary condition (see also Electrical impedance).
[src:radar-systems/radar-cross-section] This is the ratio of the tangential electric field to the tangential magnetic field on the surface, and ignores fields propagating along the surface within the coating.
[src:radar-systems/radar-cross-section] This is particularly convenient when using boundary element method calculations.
[src:radar-systems/radar-cross-section] The surface impedance can be calculated and tested separately.
[src:radar-systems/radar-cross-section] For an isotropic surface the ideal surface impedance is equal to the 377 ohm impedance of free space.
[src:radar-systems/radar-cross-section] First one does high frequency calculations to optimize the shape and find the most important features, then small calculations to find the best surface impedances in the problem areas, then reflection calculations to design coatings.
[src:radar-systems/radar-cross-section] Large numerical calculations can run too slowly for numerical optimization or can distract workers from the physics, even when massive computing power is available.
[src:radar-systems/radar-cross-section] For the case of an antenna the total RCS can be divided into two separate components as Structural Mode RCS and Antenna Mode RCS.
[src:radar-systems/radar-cross-section] The two components of the RCS relates to the two scattering phenomena that takes place at the antenna.
[src:radar-systems/radar-cross-section] When an electromagnetic signal falls on an antenna surface, some part of the electromagnetic energy is scattered back to the space.
[src:radar-systems/radar-cross-section] This is called structural mode scattering.
[src:radar-systems/radar-cross-section] The remaining part of the energy is absorbed due to the antenna effect.
[src:radar-systems/radar-cross-section] Some part of the absorbed energy is again scattered back into the space due to the impedance mismatches, called antenna mode scattering.
[src:radar-systems/radar-cross-section] For the bistatic radar configuration—transmitter and receiver separated (not co-located) -- the **bistatic radar cross section** (**BRCS**) is a function of both the transmitter-target orientation and the receiver-target orientation.
[src:radar-systems/radar-cross-section] A **normalized bistatic radar cross section** (**NBRCS**) or **bistatic normalized radar cross section** (**BNRCS**) may also be defined, similar to the monostatic NRCS.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] , used to track space objects and ballistic missiles.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] Radar of the type used for detection of aircraft.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] It rotates steadily, sweeping the airspace with a narrow beam.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] A radar system consists of a transmitter producing electromagnetic waves in the radio or microwave domain, a transmitting antenna, a receiving antenna (often the same antenna is used for transmitting and receiving) and a receiver and processor to determine properties of the objects.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] Radio waves (pulsed or continuous) from the transmitter reflect off the objects and return to the receiver, giving information about the objects' locations and speeds.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] This device was developed secretly for military use by several countries in the period before and during World War II.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] A key development was the cavity magnetron in the United Kingdom, which allowed the creation of relatively small systems with sub-meter resolution.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] Modern high tech radar systems use digital signal processing and machine learning and are capable of extracting useful information from very high noise levels.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] Other systems which are similar to radar make use of other regions of the electromagnetic spectrum.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] One example is lidar, which uses predominantly infrared light from lasers rather than radio waves.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] With the emergence of driverless vehicles, radar is expected to assist the automated platform to monitor its environment, thus preventing unwanted incidents.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] As early as 1886, German physicist Heinrich Hertz showed that radio waves could be reflected from solid objects.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] In 1895, Alexander Popov, a physics instructor at the Imperial Russian Navy school in Kronstadt, developed an apparatus using a coherer tube for detecting distant lightning strikes.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] The next year, he added a spark-gap transmitter.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] In 1897, while testing this equipment for communicating between two ships in the Baltic Sea, he took note of an interference beat caused by the passage of a third vessel.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] In his report, Popov wrote that this phenomenon might be used for detecting objects, but he did nothing more with this observation.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] The German inventor Christian Hülsmeyer was the first to use radio waves to detect "the presence of distant metallic objects".
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] In 1904, he demonstrated the feasibility of detecting a ship in dense fog, but not its distance from the transmitter.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] He obtained a patent for his detection device in April 1904 and later a patent for a related amendment for estimating the distance to the ship.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] He also obtained a British patent on 23 September 1904 for a full radar system, that he called a *telemobiloscope*.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] It operated on a 50 cm wavelength and the pulsed radar signal was created via a spark-gap.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] His system already used the classic antenna setup of horn antenna with parabolic reflector and was presented to German military officials in practical tests in Cologne and Rotterdam harbour but was rejected.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] Through his lightning experiments, Watson-Watt became an expert on the use of radio direction finding before turning his inquiry to shortwave transmission.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] Requiring a suitable receiver for such studies, he told the "new boy" Arnold Frederic Wilkins to conduct an extensive review of available shortwave units.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] Wilkins would select a General Post Office model after noting its manual's description of a "fading" effect (the common term for interference at the time) when aircraft flew overhead.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] By placing a transmitter and receiver on opposite sides of the Potomac River in 1922, U.S.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] Young discovered that ships passing through the beam path caused the received signal to fade in and out.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] Taylor submitted a report, suggesting that this phenomenon might be used to detect the presence of ships in low visibility, but the Navy did not immediately continue the work.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] Alder took out a secret provisional patent for Naval radar in 1928.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] Pollard developed a breadboard test unit, operating at 50 cm (600 MHz) and using pulsed modulation which gave successful laboratory results.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] In January 1931, a writeup on the apparatus was entered in the *Inventions Book* maintained by the Royal Engineers.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] This is the first official record in Great Britain of the technology that was used in coastal defence and was incorporated into Chain Home as Chain Home (low).
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] Before World War II, radar research was conducted in the United Kingdom, the United States, France, Germany, Italy, Japan, the Soviet Union, and the Netherlands.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] In France in 1934, following systematic studies on the split-anode magnetron, the research branch of the Compagnie générale de la télégraphie sans fil (CSF) headed by Maurice Ponte with Henri Gutton, Sylvain Berline and M.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] Hugon, began developing an obstacle-locating radio apparatus, aspects of which were installed on the ocean liner *Normandie* in 1935.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] During the same period, Soviet military engineer P.K.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] Oshchepkov, in collaboration with the Leningrad Electrotechnical Institute, produced an experimental apparatus, RAPID, capable of detecting an aircraft within 3 km of a receiver.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] The Soviets produced their first mass production radars RUS-1 and RUS-2 Redut in 1939 but further development was slowed following the arrest of Oshchepkov and his subsequent gulag sentence.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] In total, only 607 Redut stations were produced during the war.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] The first Russian airborne radar, Gneiss-2, entered into service in June 1943 on Pe-2 dive bombers.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] More than 230 Gneiss-2 stations were produced by the end of 1944.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] The French and Soviet systems, however, featured continuous-wave operation that did not provide the full performance ultimately synonymous with modern radar systems.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] Full radar evolved as a pulsed system, and the first such elementary apparatus was demonstrated in December 1934 by the American Robert M.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] Page, working at the Naval Research Laboratory.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] The following year, the United States Army successfully tested a primitive surface-to-surface radar to aim coastal battery searchlights at night.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] This design was followed by a pulsed system demonstrated in May 1935 by Rudolf Kühnhold and the firm GEMA in Germany and then another in June 1935 by an Air Ministry team led by Robert Watson-Watt in Great Britain.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] In 1935, Watson-Watt was asked to judge recent reports of a German radio-based death ray and turned the request over to Wilkins.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] Wilkins returned a set of calculations demonstrating the system was basically impossible.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] When Watson-Watt then asked what such a system might do, Wilkins recalled the earlier report about aircraft causing radio interference.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] This revelation led to the Daventry Experiment of 26 February 1935, using a powerful BBC shortwave transmitter as the source and their GPO receiver setup in a field while a bomber flew around the site.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] When the plane was clearly detected, Hugh Dowding, the Air Member for Supply and Research, was very impressed with their system's potential and funds were immediately provided for further operational development.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] Watson-Watt's team patented the device in patent GB593017.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] Development of radar greatly expanded in 1936, when Watson-Watt became superintendent of a new establishment under the British Air Ministry, Bawdsey Research Station located in Bawdsey Manor, near Felixstowe, Suffolk.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] Work there resulted in the design and installation of aircraft detection and tracking stations called "Chain Home" along the East and South coasts of England in time for the outbreak of World War II in 1939.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] This system provided the vital advance information that helped the Royal Air Force win the Battle of Britain; without it, significant numbers of fighter aircraft, which Great Britain did not have available, would always have needed to be in the air to respond quickly.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] The radar formed part of the "Dowding system" for collecting reports of enemy aircraft and coordinating the response.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] Given all required funding and development support, the team produced working radar systems in 1935 and began deployment.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] By 1936, the first five Chain Home (CH) systems were operational and by 1940 stretched across the entire UK including Northern Ireland.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] Even by standards of the era, CH was crude; instead of broadcasting and receiving from an aimed antenna, CH broadcast a signal floodlighting the entire area in front of it, and then used one of Watson-Watt's own radio direction finders to determine the direction of the returned echoes.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] This fact meant CH transmitters had to be much more powerful and have better antennas than competing systems but allowed its rapid introduction using existing technologies.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] A key development was the cavity magnetron in the UK, which allowed the creation of relatively small systems with sub-meter resolution.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] Britain shared the technology with the U.S. during the 1940 Tizard Mission.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] In April 1940, *Popular Science* showed an example of a radar unit using the Watson-Watt patent in an article on air defence.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] Also, in late 1941 *Popular Mechanics* had an article in which a U.S. scientist speculated about the British early warning system on the English east coast and came close to what it was and how it worked.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] Watson-Watt was sent to the U.S. in 1941 to advise on air defense after Japan's attack on Pearl Harbor.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] Alfred Lee Loomis organized the secret MIT Radiation Laboratory at Massachusetts Institute of Technology, Cambridge, Massachusetts which developed microwave radar technology in the years 1941–45.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] Later, in 1943, Page greatly improved radar with the monopulse technique that was used for many years in most radar applications.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] The information provided by radar includes the bearing and range (and therefore position) of the object from the radar scanner.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] It is thus used in many different fields where the need for such positioning is crucial.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] The first use of radar was for military purposes: to locate air, ground and sea targets.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] This evolved in the civilian field into applications for aircraft, ships, and automobiles.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] In aviation, aircraft can be equipped with radar devices that warn of aircraft or other obstacles in or approaching their path, display weather information, and give accurate altitude readings.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] The first commercial device fitted to aircraft was a 1938 Bell Lab unit on some United Air Lines aircraft.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] Military fighter aircraft are usually fitted with air-to-air targeting radars, to detect and target enemy aircraft.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] In addition, larger specialized military aircraft carry powerful airborne radars to observe air traffic over a wide region and direct fighter aircraft towards targets.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] Marine radars are used to measure the bearing and distance of ships to prevent collision with other ships, to navigate, and to fix their position at sea when within range of shore or other fixed references such as islands, buoys, and lightships.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] In port or in harbour, vessel traffic service radar systems are used to monitor and regulate ship movements in busy waters.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] Meteorologists use radar to monitor precipitation and wind.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] It has become the primary tool for short-term weather forecasting and watching for severe weather such as thunderstorms, tornadoes, winter storms, precipitation types, etc.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] Geologists use specialized ground-penetrating radars to map the composition of Earth's crust.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] Police forces use radar guns to monitor vehicle speeds on the roads.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] Automotive radars are used for adaptive cruise control and emergency braking on vehicles by ignoring stationary roadside objects that could cause incorrect brake application and instead measuring moving objects to prevent collision with other vehicles.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] As part of Intelligent Transport Systems, fixed-position stopped vehicle detection (SVD) radars are mounted on the roadside to detect stranded vehicles, obstructions and debris by inverting the automotive radar approach and ignoring moving objects.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] Smaller radar systems are used to detect human movement.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] Examples are breathing pattern detection for sleep monitoring and hand and finger gesture detection for computer interaction.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] Automatic door opening, light activation and intruder sensing are also common.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] A radar system has a transmitter that emits radio waves known as *radar signals* in predetermined directions.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] When these signals contact an object they are usually reflected or scattered in many directions, although some of them will be absorbed and penetrate into the target.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] Radar signals are reflected especially well by materials of considerable electrical conductivity—such as most metals, seawater, and wet ground.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] This makes the use of radar altimeters possible in certain cases.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] The radar signals that are reflected back towards the radar receiver are the desirable ones that make radar detection work.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] If the object is *moving* either toward or away from the transmitter, there will be a slight change in the frequency of the radio waves due to the Doppler effect.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] Radar receivers are usually, but not always, in the same location as the transmitter.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] The reflected radar signals captured by the receiving antenna are usually very weak.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] They can be strengthened by electronic amplifiers.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] More sophisticated methods of signal processing are also used in order to recover useful radar signals.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] The weak absorption of radio waves by the medium through which they pass is what enables radar sets to detect objects at relatively long ranges—ranges at which other electromagnetic wavelengths, such as visible light, infrared light, and ultraviolet light, are too strongly attenuated.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] Weather phenomena, such as fog, clouds, rain, falling snow, and sleet, that block visible light are usually transparent to radio waves.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] Certain radio frequencies that are absorbed or scattered by water vapour, raindrops, or atmospheric gases (especially oxygen) are avoided when designing radars, except when their detection is intended.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] Radar relies on its own transmissions rather than light from the Sun or the Moon, or from electromagnetic waves emitted by the target objects themselves, such as infrared radiation (heat).
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] This process of directing artificial radio waves towards objects is called *illumination*, although radio waves are invisible to the human eye as well as optical cameras.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] If electromagnetic waves travelling through one material meet another material, having a different dielectric constant or diamagnetic constant from the first, the waves will reflect or scatter from the boundary between the materials.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] This means that a solid object in air or in a vacuum, or a significant change in atomic density between the object and what is surrounding it, will usually scatter radar (radio) waves from its surface.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] This is particularly true for electrically conductive materials such as metal and carbon fibre, making radar well-suited to the detection of aircraft and ships.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] Radar absorbing material, containing resistive and sometimes magnetic substances, is used on military vehicles to reduce radar reflection.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] This is the radio equivalent of painting something a dark colour so that it cannot be seen by the eye at night.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] Radar waves scatter in a variety of ways depending on the size (wavelength) of the radio wave and the shape of the target.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] If the wavelength is much shorter than the target's size, the wave will bounce off in a way similar to the way light is reflected by a mirror.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] If the wavelength is much longer than the size of the target, the target may not be visible because of poor reflection.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] Low-frequency radar technology is dependent on resonances for detection, but not identification, of targets.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] This is described by Rayleigh scattering, an effect that creates Earth's blue sky and red sunsets.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] When the two length scales are comparable, there may be resonances.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] Early radars used very long wavelengths that were larger than the targets and thus received a vague signal, whereas many modern systems use shorter wavelengths (a few centimetres or less) that can image objects as small as a loaf of bread.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] Short radio waves reflect from curves and corners in a way similar to glint from a rounded piece of glass.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] The most reflective targets for short wavelengths have 90° angles between the reflective surfaces.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] A corner reflector consists of three flat surfaces meeting like the inside corner of a cube.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] The structure will reflect waves entering its opening directly back to the source.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] They are commonly used as radar reflectors to make otherwise difficult-to-detect objects easier to detect.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] Corner reflectors on boats, for example, make them more detectable to avoid collision or during a rescue.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] For similar reasons, objects intended to avoid detection will not have inside corners or surfaces and edges perpendicular to likely detection directions, which leads to "odd" looking stealth aircraft.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] These precautions do not totally eliminate reflection because of diffraction, especially at longer wavelengths.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] Half wavelength long wires or strips of conducting material, such as chaff, are very reflective but do not direct the scattered energy back toward the source.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] The extent to which an object reflects or scatters radio waves is called its radar cross-section.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] In the common case where the transmitter and the receiver are at the same location, *R*t = *R*r and the term *R*t² *R*r² can be replaced by *R*4, where *R* is the range.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] This shows that the received power declines as the fourth power of the range, which means that the received power from distant targets is relatively very small.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] Additional filtering and pulse integration modifies the radar equation slightly for pulse-Doppler radar performance, which can be used to increase detection range and reduce transmit power.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] The equation above with *F* = 1 is a simplification for transmission in a vacuum without interference.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] The propagation factor accounts for the effects of multipath and shadowing and depends on the details of the environment.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] In a real-world situation, pathloss effects are also considered.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] Frequency shift is caused by motion that changes the number of wavelengths between the reflector and the radar.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] This can degrade or enhance radar performance depending upon how it affects the detection process.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] As an example, moving target indication can interact with Doppler to produce signal cancellation at certain radial velocities, which degrades performance.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] Sea-based radar systems, semi-active radar homing, active radar homing, weather radar, military aircraft, and radar astronomy rely on the Doppler effect to enhance performance.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] This produces information about target velocity during the detection process.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] This also allows small objects to be detected in an environment containing much larger nearby slow moving objects.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] Doppler shift depends upon whether the radar configuration is active or passive.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] Active radar transmits a signal that is reflected back to the receiver.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] Passive radar depends upon the object sending a signal to the receiver.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] Only the radial component of the velocity is relevant.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] When the reflector is moving at right angle to the radar beam, it has no relative velocity.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] Objects moving parallel to the radar beam produce the maximum Doppler frequency shift.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] When the transmit frequency ( $F_{T}$ ) is pulsed, using a pulse repeat frequency of $F_{R}$ , the resulting frequency spectrum will contain harmonic frequencies above and below $F_{T}$ with a distance of $F_{R}$ .
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] As an example, a Doppler weather radar with a pulse rate of 2 kHz and transmit frequency of 1 GHz can reliably measure weather speed up to at most 150 m/s (340 mph), thus cannot reliably determine radial velocity of aircraft moving 1,000 m/s (2,200 mph).
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] In all electromagnetic radiation, the electric field is perpendicular to the direction of propagation, and the electric field direction is the polarization of the wave.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] For a transmitted radar signal, the polarization can be controlled to yield different effects.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] Radars use horizontal, vertical, linear, and circular polarization to detect different types of reflections.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] For example, circular polarization is used to minimize the interference caused by rain.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] Linear polarization returns usually indicate metal surfaces.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] Random polarization returns usually indicate a fractal surface, such as rocks or soil, and are used by navigation radars.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] A radar beam follows a linear path in vacuum but follows a somewhat curved path in atmosphere due to variation in the refractive index of air, which is called the radar horizon.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] Even when the beam is emitted parallel to the ground, the beam rises above the ground as the curvature of the Earth sinks below the horizon.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] Furthermore, the signal is attenuated by the medium the beam crosses, and the beam disperses.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] Signal noise is an internal source of random variations in the signal, which is generated by all electronic components.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] Reflected signals decline rapidly as distance increases, so noise introduces a radar range limitation.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] The noise floor and signal-to-noise ratio are two different measures of performance that affect range performance.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] Reflectors that are too far away produce too little signal to exceed the noise floor and cannot be detected.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] Detection requires a signal that exceeds the noise floor by at least the signal-to-noise ratio.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] Noise typically appears as random variations superimposed on the desired echo signal received in the radar receiver.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] The lower the power of the desired signal, the more difficult it is to discern it from the noise.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] The noise figure is a measure of the noise produced by a receiver compared to an ideal receiver, and this needs to be minimized.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] Shot noise is produced by electrons in transit across a discontinuity, which occurs in all detectors.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] Shot noise is the dominant source in most receivers.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] There will also be flicker noise caused by electron transit through amplification devices, which is reduced using heterodyne amplification.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] Another reason for heterodyne processing is that for fixed fractional bandwidth, the instantaneous bandwidth increases linearly in frequency.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] The one notable exception to heterodyne (downconversion) radar systems is ultra-wideband radar.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] Here a single cycle, or transient wave, is used similar to UWB communications, see List of UWB channels.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] Noise is also generated by external sources, most importantly the natural thermal radiation of the background surrounding the target of interest.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] In modern radar systems, the internal noise is typically about equal to or lower than the external noise.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] An exception is if the radar is aimed upwards at clear sky, where the scene is so "cold" that it generates very little thermal noise.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] The thermal noise is given by *k*B *T* *B*, where *T* is temperature, *B* is bandwidth (post matched filter) and *k*B is the Boltzmann constant.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] There is an appealing intuitive interpretation of this relationship in a radar.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] Matched filtering allows the entire energy received from a target to be compressed into a single bin (be it a range, Doppler, elevation, or azimuth bin).
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] On the surface it appears that then within a fixed interval of time, perfect, error free, detection could be obtained.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] This is done by compressing all energy into an infinitesimal time slice.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] What limits this approach in the real world is that, while time is arbitrarily divisible, current is not.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] The quantum of electrical energy is an electron, and so the best that can be done is to match filter all energy into a single electron.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] Since the electron is moving at a certain temperature (Planck spectrum) this noise source cannot be further eroded.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] Ultimately, radar, like all macro-scale entities, is profoundly impacted by quantum theory.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] Noise is random and target signals are not.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] Signal processing can take advantage of this phenomenon to reduce the noise floor using two strategies.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] The kind of signal integration used with moving target indication can improve noise up to ${\sqrt {2}}$ for each stage.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] The signal can also be split among multiple filters for pulse-Doppler signal processing, which reduces the noise floor by the number of filters.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] These improvements depend upon coherence.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] Radar systems must overcome unwanted signals in order to focus on the targets of interest.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] These unwanted signals may originate from internal and external sources, both passive and active.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] The ability of the radar system to overcome these unwanted signals defines its signal-to-noise ratio (SNR).
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] SNR is defined as the ratio of the signal power to the noise power within the desired signal; it compares the level of a desired target signal to the level of background noise (atmospheric noise and noise generated within the receiver).
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] The higher a system's SNR the better it is at discriminating actual targets from noise signals.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] Clutter refers to radio frequency (RF) echoes returned from targets which are uninteresting to radar operators.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] Such targets include man-made objects such as buildings and — intentionally — by radar countermeasures such as chaff.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] Such targets also include natural objects such as ground, sea, and — when not being tasked for meteorological purposes — precipitation, hail spike, dust storms, animals (especially birds), turbulence in the atmospheric circulation, and meteor trails.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] Radar clutter can also be caused by other atmospheric phenomena, such as disturbances in the ionosphere caused by geomagnetic storms or other space weather events.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] This phenomenon is especially apparent near the geomagnetic poles, where the action of the solar wind on the earth's magnetosphere produces convection patterns in the ionospheric plasma.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] Radar clutter can degrade the ability of over-the-horizon radar to detect targets.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] Some clutter may also be caused by a long radar waveguide between the radar transceiver and the antenna.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] In a typical plan position indicator (PPI) radar with a rotating antenna, this will usually be seen as a "sun" or "sunburst" in the center of the display as the receiver responds to echoes from dust particles and misguided RF in the waveguide.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] Adjusting the timing between when the transmitter sends a pulse and when the receiver stage is enabled will generally reduce the sunburst without affecting the accuracy of the range since most sunburst is caused by a diffused transmit pulse reflected before it leaves the antenna.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] Clutter is considered a passive interference source since it only appears in response to radar signals sent by the radar.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] Clutter is detected and neutralized in several ways.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] Clutter tends to appear static between radar scans; on subsequent scan echoes, desirable targets will appear to move, and all stationary echoes can be eliminated.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] Sea clutter can be reduced by using horizontal polarization, while rain is reduced with circular polarization (meteorological radars wish for the opposite effect, and therefore use linear polarization to detect precipitation).
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] Other methods attempt to increase the signal-to-clutter ratio.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] Clutter moves with the wind or is stationary.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] The most effective clutter reduction technique is pulse-Doppler radar.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] Doppler separates clutter from aircraft and spacecraft using a frequency spectrum, so individual signals can be separated from multiple reflectors located in the same volume using velocity differences.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] Another technique uses a moving target indicator that subtracts the received signal from two successive pulses using phase to reduce signals from slow-moving objects.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] This can be adapted for systems that lack a coherent transmitter, such as time-domain pulse-amplitude radar.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] Constant false alarm rate, a form of automatic gain control (AGC), is a method that relies on clutter returns far outnumbering echoes from targets of interest.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] The receiver's gain is automatically adjusted to maintain a constant level of overall visible clutter.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] While this does not help detect targets masked by stronger surrounding clutter, it does help to distinguish strong target sources.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] In the past, radar AGC was electronically controlled and affected the gain of the entire radar receiver.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] As radars evolved, AGC became computer-software-controlled and affected the gain with greater granularity in specific detection cells.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] Clutter may also originate from multipath echoes from valid targets caused by ground reflection, atmospheric ducting or ionospheric reflection/refraction (e.g., anomalous propagation).
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] This clutter type is especially bothersome since it appears to move and behave like other normal (point) targets of interest.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] In a typical scenario, an aircraft echo is reflected from the ground below, appearing to the receiver as an identical target below the correct one.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] The radar may try to unify the targets, reporting the target at an incorrect height, or eliminating it on the basis of jitter or a physical impossibility.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] Terrain bounce jamming exploits this response by amplifying the radar signal and directing it downward.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] These problems can be overcome by incorporating a ground map of the radar's surroundings and eliminating all echoes which appear to originate below ground or above a certain height.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] Monopulse can be improved by altering the elevation algorithm used at low elevation.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] In newer air traffic control radar equipment, algorithms are used to identify the false targets by comparing the current pulse returns to those adjacent, as well as calculating return improbabilities.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] Radar jamming refers to radio frequency signals originating from sources outside the radar, transmitting in the radar's frequency and thereby masking targets of interest.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] Jamming may be intentional, as with an electronic warfare tactic, or unintentional, as with friendly forces operating equipment that transmits using the same frequency range.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] Jamming is considered an active interference source, since it is initiated by elements outside the radar and in general unrelated to the radar signals.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] Jammers therefore can be much less powerful than their jammed radars and still effectively mask targets along the line of sight from the jammer to the radar (*mainlobe jamming*).
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] Jammers have an added effect of affecting radars along other lines of sight through the radar receiver's sidelobes (*sidelobe jamming*).
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] Mainlobe jamming can generally only be reduced by narrowing the mainlobe solid angle and cannot fully be eliminated when directly facing a jammer which uses the same frequency and polarization as the radar.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] Sidelobe jamming can be overcome by reducing receiving sidelobes in the radar antenna design and by using an omnidirectional antenna to detect and disregard non-mainlobe signals.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p01] Other anti-jamming techniques are frequency hopping and polarization.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p02] One way to obtain a distance measurement (ranging) is based on the time-of-flight: transmit a short pulse of radio signal (electromagnetic radiation) and measure the time it takes for the reflection to return.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p02] The distance is one-half the round trip time multiplied by the speed of the signal.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p02] The factor of one-half comes from the fact that the signal has to travel to the object and back again.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p02] Since radio waves travel at the speed of light, accurate distance measurement requires high-speed electronics.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p02] In most cases, the receiver does not detect the return while the signal is being transmitted.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p02] Through the use of a duplexer, the radar switches between transmitting and receiving at a predetermined rate.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p02] A similar effect imposes a maximum range as well.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p02] In order to maximize range, longer times between pulses should be used, referred to as a pulse repetition time, or its reciprocal, pulse repetition frequency.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p02] These two effects tend to be at odds with each other, and it is not easy to combine both good short range and good long range in a single radar.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p02] This is because the short pulses needed for a good minimum range broadcast have less total energy, making the returns much smaller and the target harder to detect.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p02] This could be offset by using more pulses, but this would shorten the maximum range.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p02] So each radar uses a particular type of signal.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p02] Long-range radars tend to use long pulses with long delays between them, and short range radars use smaller pulses with less time between them.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p02] As electronics have improved many radars now can change their pulse repetition frequency, thereby changing their range.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p02] The newest radars fire two pulses during one cell, one for short range (about 10 km (6.2 miles)) and a separate signal for longer ranges (about 100 km (62 miles)).
[src:radar-systems/radar-p02] Distance may also be measured as a function of time.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p02] The **radar mile** is the time it takes for a radar pulse to travel one nautical mile, reflect off a target, and return to the radar antenna.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p02] Since a nautical mile is defined as 1,852 m, then dividing this distance by the speed of light (299,792,458 m/s), and then multiplying the result by 2 yields a result of 12.36 μs in duration.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p02] Another form of distance measuring radar is based on frequency modulation.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p02] In these systems, the frequency of the transmitted signal is changed over time.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p02] Since the signal takes a finite time to travel to and from the target, the received signal is a different frequency than what the transmitter is broadcasting at the time the reflected signal arrives back at the radar.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p02] By comparing the frequency of the two signals the difference can be easily measured.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p02] This is easily accomplished with very high accuracy even in 1940s electronics.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p02] A further advantage is that the radar can operate effectively at relatively low frequencies.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p02] This was important in the early development of this type when high-frequency signal generation was difficult or expensive.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p02] This technique can be used in continuous wave radar and is often found in aircraft radar altimeters.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p02] In these systems a "carrier" radar signal is frequency modulated in a predictable way, typically varying up and down with a sine wave or sawtooth pattern at audio frequencies.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p02] The modulation index riding on the receive signal is proportional to the time delay between the radar and the reflector.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p02] The frequency shift becomes greater with greater time delay.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p02] The frequency shift is directly proportional to the distance travelled.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p02] That distance can be displayed on an instrument, and it may also be available via the transponder.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p02] This signal processing is similar to that used in speed detecting Doppler radar.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p02] Example systems using this approach are AZUSA, MISTRAM, and UDOP.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p02] Terrestrial radar uses low-power FM signals that cover a larger frequency range.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p02] The multiple reflections are analyzed mathematically for pattern changes with multiple passes creating a computerized synthetic image.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p02] Doppler effects are used which allows slow moving objects to be detected as well as largely eliminating "noise" from the surfaces of bodies of water.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p02] The two techniques outlined above both have their disadvantages.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p02] The pulse timing technique has an inherent tradeoff in that the accuracy of the distance measurement is inversely related to the length of the pulse, while the energy, and thus direction range, is directly related.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p02] Increasing power for longer range while maintaining accuracy demands extremely high peak power, with 1960s early warning radars often operating in the tens of megawatts.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p02] The continuous wave methods spread this energy out in time and thus require much lower peak power compared to pulse techniques, but requires some method of allowing the sent and received signals to operate at the same time, often demanding two separate antennas.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p02] The introduction of new electronics in the 1960s allowed the two techniques to be combined.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p02] It starts with a longer pulse that is also frequency modulated.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p02] Spreading the broadcast energy out in time means lower peak energies can be used, with modern examples typically on the order of tens of kilowatts.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p02] On reception, the signal is sent into a system that delays different frequencies by different times.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p02] The resulting output is a much shorter pulse that is suitable for accurate distance measurement, while also compressing the received energy into a much higher energy peak and thus improving the signal-to-noise ratio.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p02] The technique is largely universal on modern large radars.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p02] Speed is the change in distance to an object with respect to time.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p02] Thus the existing system for measuring distance, combined with a memory capacity to see where the target last was, is enough to measure speed.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p02] At one time the memory consisted of a user making grease pencil marks on the radar screen and then calculating the speed using a slide rule.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p02] Modern radar systems perform the equivalent operation faster and more accurately using computers.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p02] If the transmitter's output is coherent (phase synchronized), there is another effect that can be used to make almost instant speed measurements (no memory is required), known as the Doppler effect.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p02] Most modern radar systems use this principle into Doppler radar and pulse-Doppler radar systems (weather radar, military radar).
[src:radar-systems/radar-p02] The Doppler effect is only able to determine the relative speed of the target along the line of sight from the radar to the target.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p02] Any component of target velocity perpendicular to the line of sight cannot be determined by using the Doppler effect alone, but it can be determined by tracking the target's azimuth over time.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p02] It is possible to make a Doppler radar without any pulsing, known as a continuous-wave radar (CW radar), by sending out a very pure signal of a known frequency.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p02] CW radar is ideal for determining the radial component of a target's velocity.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p02] CW radar is typically used by traffic enforcement to measure vehicle speed quickly and accurately where the range is not important.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p02] When using a pulsed radar, the variation between the phase of successive returns gives the distance the target has moved between pulses, and thus its speed can be calculated.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p02] Other mathematical developments in radar signal processing include time-frequency analysis (Weyl Heisenberg or wavelet), as well as the chirplet transform which makes use of the change of frequency of returns from moving targets ("chirp").
[src:radar-systems/radar-p02] Pulse-Doppler signal processing includes frequency filtering in the detection process.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p02] The space between each transmit pulse is divided into range cells or range gates.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p02] Each cell is filtered independently much like the process used by a spectrum analyzer to produce the display showing different frequencies.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p02] Each different distance produces a different spectrum.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p02] These spectra are used to perform the detection process.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p02] This is required to achieve acceptable performance in hostile environments involving weather, terrain, and electronic countermeasures.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p02] The primary purpose is to measure both the amplitude and frequency of the aggregate reflected signal from multiple distances.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p02] This is used with weather radar to measure radial wind velocity and precipitation rate in each different volume of air.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p02] This is linked with computing systems to produce a real-time electronic weather map.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p02] Aircraft safety depends upon continuous access to accurate weather radar information that is used to prevent injuries and accidents.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p02] Coherency requirements are not as strict as those for military systems because individual signals ordinarily do not need to be separated.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p02] Less sophisticated filtering is required, and range ambiguity processing is not normally needed with weather radar in comparison with military radar intended to track air vehicles.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p02] The alternate purpose is "look-down/shoot-down" capability required to improve military air combat survivability.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p02] Pulse-Doppler is also used for ground based surveillance radar required to defend personnel and vehicles.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p02] Pulse-doppler signal processing increases the maximum detection distance using less radiation close to aircraft pilots, shipboard personnel, infantry, and artillery.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p02] Reflections from terrain, water, and weather produce signals much larger than aircraft and missiles, which allows fast moving vehicles to hide using nap-of-the-earth flying techniques and stealth technology to avoid detection until an attack vehicle is too close to destroy.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p02] Pulse-Doppler signal processing incorporates more sophisticated electronic filtering that safely eliminates this kind of weakness.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p02] This requires the use of medium pulse-repetition frequency with phase coherent hardware that has a large dynamic range.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p02] Military applications require medium PRF which prevents range from being determined directly, and range ambiguity resolution processing is required to identify the true range of all reflected signals.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p02] Radial movement is usually linked with Doppler frequency to produce a lock signal that cannot be produced by radar jamming signals.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p02] Pulse-Doppler signal processing also produces audible signals that can be used for threat identification.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p02] Signal processing is employed in radar systems to reduce the radar interference effects.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p02] Signal processing techniques include moving target indication, Pulse-Doppler signal processing, moving target detection processors, correlation with secondary surveillance radar targets, space-time adaptive processing, and track-before-detect.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p02] Constant false alarm rate and digital terrain model processing are also used in clutter environments.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p02] A track algorithm is a radar performance enhancement strategy.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p02] Tracking algorithms provide the ability to predict the future position of multiple moving objects based on the history of the individual positions being reported by sensor systems.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p02] Historical information is accumulated and used to predict future position for use with air traffic control, threat estimation, combat system doctrine, gun aiming, and missile guidance.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p02] Position data is accumulated by radar sensors over the span of a few minutes.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p02] Radar video returns from aircraft can be subjected to a plot extraction process whereby spurious and interfering signals are discarded.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p02] A sequence of target returns can be monitored through a device known as a plot extractor.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p02] The non-relevant real time returns can be removed from the displayed information and a single plot displayed.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p02] In some radar systems, or alternatively in the command and control system to which the radar is connected, a radar tracker is used to associate the sequence of plots belonging to individual targets and estimate the targets' headings and speeds.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p02] Radio signals broadcast from a single antenna will spread out in all directions, and likewise a single antenna will receive signals equally from all directions.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p02] This leaves the radar with the problem of deciding where the target object is located.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p02] Early systems tended to use omnidirectional broadcast antennas, with directional receiver antennas which were pointed in various directions.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p02] For instance, the first system to be deployed, Chain Home, used two straight antennas at right angles for reception, each on a different display.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p02] The maximum return would be detected with an antenna at right angles to the target, and a minimum with the antenna pointed directly at it (end on).
[src:radar-systems/radar-p02] The operator could determine the direction to a target by rotating the antenna so one display showed a maximum while the other showed a minimum.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p02] One serious limitation with this type of solution is that the broadcast is sent out in all directions, so the amount of energy in the direction being examined is a small part of that transmitted.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p02] To get a reasonable amount of power on the "target", the transmitting aerial should also be directional.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p02] More modern systems use a steerable parabolic "dish" to create a tight broadcast beam, typically using the same dish as the receiver.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p02] Such systems often combine two radar frequencies in the same antenna in order to allow automatic steering, or *radar lock*.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p02] Parabolic reflectors can be either symmetric parabolas or spoiled parabolas: Symmetric parabolic antennas produce a narrow "pencil" beam in both the X and Y dimensions and consequently have a higher gain.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p02] The NEXRAD Pulse-Doppler weather radar uses a symmetric antenna to perform detailed volumetric scans of the atmosphere.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p02] Spoiled parabolic antennas produce a narrow beam in one dimension and a relatively wide beam in the other.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p02] This feature is useful if target detection over a wide range of angles is more important than target location in three dimensions.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p02] Most 2D surveillance radars use a spoiled parabolic antenna with a narrow azimuthal beamwidth and wide vertical beamwidth.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p02] This beam configuration allows the radar operator to detect an aircraft at a specific azimuth but at an indeterminate height.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p02] Conversely, so-called "nodder" height finding radars use a dish with a narrow vertical beamwidth and wide azimuthal beamwidth to detect an aircraft at a specific height but with low azimuthal precision.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p02] Applied similarly to the parabolic reflector, the slotted waveguide is moved mechanically to scan and is particularly suitable for non-tracking surface scan systems, where the vertical pattern may remain constant.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p02] Owing to its lower cost and less wind exposure, shipboard, airport surface, and harbour surveillance radars now use this approach in preference to a parabolic antenna.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p02] Another method of steering is used in a phased array radar.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p02] Phased array antennas are composed of evenly spaced similar antenna elements, such as aerials or rows of slotted waveguide.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p02] Each antenna element or group of antenna elements incorporates a discrete phase shift that produces a phase gradient across the array.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p02] For example, array elements producing a 5 degree phase shift for each wavelength across the array face will produce a beam pointed 5 degrees away from the centerline perpendicular to the array face.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p02] Signals travelling along that beam will be reinforced.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p02] Signals offset from that beam will be cancelled.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p02] The amount of reinforcement is antenna gain.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p02] The amount of cancellation is side-lobe suppression.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p02] Phased array radars have been in use since the earliest years of radar in World War II (Mammut radar), but electronic device limitations led to poor performance.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p02] Phased array radars were originally used for missile defence (see for example Safeguard Program).
[src:radar-systems/radar-p02] They are the heart of the ship-borne Aegis Combat System and the Patriot Missile System.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p02] The massive redundancy associated with having a large number of array elements increases reliability at the expense of gradual performance degradation that occurs as individual phase elements fail.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p02] To a lesser extent, phased array radars have been used in weather surveillance.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p02] As of 2017, NOAA plans to implement a national network of multi-function phased array radars throughout the United States within 10 years, for meteorological studies and flight monitoring.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p02] Phased array antennas can be built to conform to specific shapes, like missiles, infantry support vehicles, ships, and aircraft.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p02] As the price of electronics has fallen, phased array radars have become more common.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p02] Almost all modern military radar systems are based on phased arrays, where the small additional cost is offset by the improved reliability of a system with no moving parts.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p02] Traditional moving-antenna designs are still widely used in roles where cost is a significant factor such as air traffic surveillance and similar systems.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p02] Phased array radars are valued for use in aircraft since they can track multiple targets.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p02] The first aircraft to use a phased array radar was the B-1B Lancer.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p02] The first fighter aircraft to use phased array radar was the Mikoyan MiG-31.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p02] The MiG-31M's SBI-16 Zaslon passive electronically scanned array radar was considered to be the world's most powerful fighter radar, until the AN/APG-77 active electronically scanned array was introduced on the Lockheed Martin F-22 Raptor.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p02] Phased-array interferometry or aperture synthesis techniques, using an array of separate dishes that are phased into a single effective aperture, are not typical for radar applications, although they are widely used in radio astronomy.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p02] Because of the thinned array curse, such multiple aperture arrays, when used in transmitters, result in narrow beams at the expense of reducing the total power transmitted to the target.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p02] In principle, such techniques could increase spatial resolution, but the lower power means that this is generally not effective.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p02] Aperture synthesis by post-processing motion data from a single moving source, on the other hand, is widely used in space and airborne radar systems.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p02] Antennas generally have to be sized similar to the wavelength of the operational frequency, normally within an order of magnitude.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p02] This provides a strong incentive to use shorter wavelengths as this will result in smaller antennas.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p02] Shorter wavelengths also result in higher resolution due to diffraction, meaning the shaped reflector seen on most radars can also be made smaller for any desired beamwidth.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p02] Opposing the move to smaller wavelengths are a number of practical issues.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p02] For one, the electronics needed to produce high power very short wavelengths were generally more complex and expensive than the electronics needed for longer wavelengths or did not exist at all.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p02] Another issue is that the radar equation's effective aperture figure means that for any given antenna (or reflector) size will be more efficient at longer wavelengths.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p02] Additionally, shorter wavelengths may interact with molecules or raindrops in the air, scattering the signal.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p02] Very long wavelengths also have additional diffraction effects that make them suitable for over the horizon radars.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p02] For this reason, a wide variety of wavelengths are used in different roles.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p02] The traditional band names originated as code-names during World War II and are still in military and aviation use throughout the world.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p02] They have been adopted in the United States by the Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers and internationally by the International Telecommunication Union.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p02] Most countries have additional regulations to control which parts of each band are available for civilian or military use.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p02] Other users of the radio spectrum, such as the broadcasting and electronic countermeasures industries, have replaced the traditional military designations with their own systems.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p02] Modulators act to provide the waveform of the RF-pulse.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p02] Coherent microwave amplifiers operating above 1,000 watts microwave output, like travelling wave tubes and klystrons, require liquid coolant.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p02] The electron beam must contain 5 to 10 times more power than the microwave output, which can produce enough heat to generate plasma.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p02] This plasma flows from the collector toward the cathode.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p02] The same magnetic focusing that guides the electron beam forces the plasma into the path of the electron beam but flowing in the opposite direction.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p02] This introduces FM modulation which degrades Doppler performance.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p02] To prevent this, liquid coolant with minimum pressure and flow rate is required, and deionized water is normally used in most high power surface radar systems that use Doppler processing.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p02] Coolanol (silicate ester) was used in several military radars in the 1970s.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p02] However, it is hygroscopic, leading to hydrolysis and formation of highly flammable alcohol.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p02] Navy aircraft in 1978 was attributed to a silicate ester fire.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p02] Navy has instituted a program named Pollution Prevention (P2) to eliminate or reduce the volume and toxicity of waste, air emissions, and effluent discharges.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p02] Because of this, Coolanol is used less often today.
[src:radar-systems/radar-p02] Radar come in a variety of configurations in the emitter, the receiver, the antenna, wavelength, scan strategies, etc.
[src:radar-systems/radar-tracker] A **radar tracker** is a component of a radar system, or an associated command and control (C2) system, that associates consecutive radar observations of the same target into tracks.
[src:radar-systems/radar-tracker] It is particularly useful when the radar system is reporting data from several different targets or when it is necessary to combine the data from several different radars or other sensors for data fusion.
[src:radar-systems/radar-tracker] A classical rotating air surveillance radar system detects target echoes against a background of noise.
[src:radar-systems/radar-tracker] It reports these detections (known as "plots") in polar coordinates representing the range and bearing of the target.
[src:radar-systems/radar-tracker] In addition, noise in the radar receiver will occasionally exceed the detection threshold of the radar's constant false alarm rate detector and be incorrectly reported as targets (known as false alarms).
[src:radar-systems/radar-tracker] The role of the radar tracker is to monitor consecutive updates from the radar system (which typically occur once every few seconds, as the antenna rotates) and to determine those sequences of plots belonging to the same target, whilst rejecting any plots believed to be false alarms.
[src:radar-systems/radar-tracker] In addition, the radar tracker is able to use the sequence of plots to estimate the current speed and heading of the target.
[src:radar-systems/radar-tracker] When several targets are present, the radar tracker aims to provide one track for each target, with the track history often being used to indicate where the target has come from.
[src:radar-systems/radar-tracker] When multiple radar systems are connected to one reporting post, a *multiradar tracker* is often used to monitor the updates from all of the radars and form tracks from the combination of detections.
[src:radar-systems/radar-tracker] In this configuration, the tracks are often more accurate than those formed from single radars, as a greater number of detections can be used to estimate the tracks.
[src:radar-systems/radar-tracker] In addition to associating plots, rejecting false alarms and estimating heading and speed, the radar tracker also acts as a filter, in which errors in the individual radar measurements are smoothed out.
[src:radar-systems/radar-tracker] In essence, the radar tracker fits a smooth curve to the reported plots and, if done correctly, can increase the overall accuracy of the radar system.
[src:radar-systems/radar-tracker] There are many different mathematical algorithms used for implementing a radar tracker, of varying levels of sophistication.
[src:radar-systems/radar-tracker] Perhaps the most important step is the updating of tracks with new plots.
[src:radar-systems/radar-tracker] Using this information, the radar tracker attempts to update the track by forming a weighted average of the current reported position from the radar (which has unknown errors) and the last predicted position of the target from the tracker (which also has unknown errors).
[src:radar-systems/radar-tracker] In the real world, a radar tracker typically faces a combination of all of these effects; this has led to the development of an increasingly sophisticated set of algorithms to resolve the problem.
[src:radar-systems/radar-tracker] Due to the need to form radar tracks in real time, usually for several hundred targets at once, the deployment of radar tracking algorithms has typically been limited by the available computational power.
[src:radar-systems/radar-tracker] In this step of the processing, the radar tracker seeks to determine which plots should be used to update which tracks.
[src:radar-systems/radar-tracker] In many approaches, a given plot can only be used to update one track.
[src:radar-systems/radar-tracker] However, in other approaches a plot can be used to update several tracks, recognising the uncertainty in knowing to which track the plot belongs.
[src:radar-systems/radar-tracker] Having updated the estimates, it is possible to try to associate the plots to tracks.
[src:radar-systems/radar-tracker] Once a track has been associated with a plot, it moves to the *track smoothing* stage, where the track prediction and associated plot are combined to provide a new, smoothed estimate of the target location.
[src:radar-systems/radar-tracker] Having completed this process, some plots will remain unassociated with existing tracks and some tracks will remain without updates.
[src:radar-systems/radar-tracker] This leads to the steps of *track initiation* and *track maintenance*.
[src:radar-systems/radar-tracker] Track initiation is the process of creating a new radar track from an unassociated radar plot.
[src:radar-systems/radar-tracker] When the tracker is first switched on, all the initial radar plots are used to create new tracks, but once the tracker is running, only those plots that couldn't be used to update an existing track are used to spawn new tracks.
[src:radar-systems/radar-tracker] Typically a new track is given the status of *tentative* until plots from subsequent radar updates have been successfully associated with the new track.
[src:radar-systems/radar-tracker] Tentative tracks are not shown to the operator and so they provide a means of preventing false tracks from appearing on the screen - at the expense of some delay in the first reporting of a track.
[src:radar-systems/radar-tracker] Once several updates have been received, the track is *confirmed* and displayed to the operator.
[src:radar-systems/radar-tracker] The most common criterion for promoting a tentative track to a confirmed track is the "M-of-N rule", which states that during the last N radar updates, at least M plots must have been associated with the tentative track - with M=3 and N=5 being typical values.
[src:radar-systems/radar-tracker] More sophisticated approaches may use a statistical approach in which a track becomes confirmed when, for instance, its covariance matrix falls to a given size.
[src:radar-systems/radar-tracker] A variation of JPDA called JIPDA also estimates target existence, therefore handling plot-to-track, initialization, and maintenance.
[src:radar-systems/radar-tracker] Track maintenance is the process in which a decision is made about whether to end the life of a track.
[src:radar-systems/radar-tracker] If a track was not associated with a plot during the plot to track association phase, then there is a chance that the target may no longer exist (for instance, an aircraft may have landed or flown out of radar cover).
[src:radar-systems/radar-tracker] Alternatively, however, there is a chance that the radar may have just failed to see the target at that update, but will find it again on the next update.
[src:radar-systems/radar-tracker] In this important step, the latest track prediction is combined with the associated plot to provide a new, improved estimate of the target state as well as a revised estimate of the errors in this prediction.
[src:radar-systems/radar-tracker] There is a wide variety of algorithms, of differing complexity and computational load, that can be used for this process.
[src:radar-systems/radar-tracker] An early tracking approach, using an alpha beta filter, that assumed fixed covariance errors and a constant-speed, non-maneuvering target model to update tracks.
[src:radar-systems/radar-tracker] The role of the Kalman Filter is to take the current known state (i.e., position, heading, speed and possibly acceleration) of the target and predict the new state of the target at the time of the most recent radar measurement.
[src:radar-systems/radar-tracker] In making this prediction, it also updates its estimate of its own uncertainty (i.e., errors) in this prediction.
[src:radar-systems/radar-tracker] It then forms a weighted average of this prediction of state and the latest measurement of state, taking account of the known measurement errors of the radar and its own uncertainty in the target motion models.
[src:radar-systems/radar-tracker] Finally, it updates its estimate of its uncertainty of the state estimate.
[src:radar-systems/radar-tracker] A key assumption in the mathematics of the Kalman filter is that measurement equations (i.e., the relationship between the radar measurements and the target state) and the state equations (i.e., the equations for predicting a future state based on the current state) are linear.
[src:radar-systems/radar-tracker] The Kalman filter assumes that the measurement errors of the radar, and the errors in its target motion model, and the errors in its state estimate are all zero-mean with known covariance.
[src:radar-systems/radar-tracker] This means that all of these sources of errors can be represented by a covariance matrix.
[src:radar-systems/radar-tracker] The mathematics of the Kalman filter is therefore concerned with propagating these covariance matrices and using them to form the weighted sum of prediction and measurement.
[src:radar-systems/radar-tracker] In situations where the target motion conforms well to the underlying model, there is a tendency of the Kalman filter to become "overconfident" of its own predictions and to start to ignore the radar measurements.
[src:radar-systems/radar-tracker] If the target then manoeuvres, the filter will fail to follow the manoeuvre.
[src:radar-systems/radar-tracker] It is therefore common practice when implementing the filter to arbitrarily increase the magnitude of the state estimate covariance matrix slightly at each update to prevent this.
[src:radar-systems/radar-tracker] The MHT allows a track to be updated by more than one plot at each update, spawning multiple possible tracks.
[src:radar-systems/radar-tracker] As each radar update is received every possible track can be potentially updated with every new update.
[src:radar-systems/radar-tracker] Over time, the track branches into many possible directions.
[src:radar-systems/radar-tracker] The MHT calculates the probability of each potential track and typically only reports the most probable of all the tracks.
[src:radar-systems/radar-tracker] For reasons of finite computer memory and computational power, the MHT typically includes some approach for deleting the most unlikely potential track updates.
[src:radar-systems/radar-tracker] The MHT is designed for situations in which the target motion model is very unpredictable, as all potential track updates are considered.
[src:radar-systems/radar-tracker] For this reason, it is popular for problems of ground target tracking in Airborne Ground Surveillance (AGS) systems.
[src:radar-systems/radar-tracker] The MHT calculates not only the probabilities of previously-detected tracks, but also the probabilities of false alarms and new tracks.
[src:radar-systems/radar-tracker] As a result, it might handle multiple parts of the radar tracker algorithm, i.e., the plot-to-track, the smoothing, and the initialization.
[src:radar-systems/radar-tracker] MHT can be implemented as either hypothesis-oriented or track-oriented.
[src:radar-systems/radar-tracker] The latter type organizes hypotheses into trees, and each track has a tree.
[src:radar-systems/radar-tracker] TOMHT typically does not handle initialization and termination.
[src:radar-systems/radar-tracker] The IMM is an estimator which can either be used by MHT or JPDAF.
[src:radar-systems/radar-tracker] IMM uses two or more Kalman filters which run in parallel, each using a different model for target motion or errors.
[src:radar-systems/radar-tracker] The IMM forms an optimal weighted sum of the output of all the filters and is able to rapidly adjust to target maneuvers.
[src:radar-systems/radar-tracker] While MHT or JPDAF handles the association and track maintenance, an IMM helps MHT or JPDAF in obtaining a filtered estimate of the target position.
[src:radar-systems/radar-tracker] Non-linear tracking algorithms use a Non-linear filter to cope with the situation where the measurements have a non-linear relationship to the final track coordinates, where the errors are non-Gaussian, or where the motion update model is non-linear.
[src:radar-systems/radar-tracker] The EKF is an extension of the Kalman filter to cope with cases where the relationship between the radar measurements and the track coordinates, or the track coordinates and the motion model, is non-linear.
[src:radar-systems/radar-tracker] In this case, the relationship between the measurements and the state is of the form h=f(x) (where h is the vector of measurements, x is the target state and f(.) is the function relating the two).
[src:radar-systems/radar-tracker] Similarly, the relationship between the future state and the current state is of the form x(t+1)=g(x(t)) (where x(t) is the state at time t and g(.) is the function that predicts the future state).
[src:radar-systems/radar-tracker] To handle these non-linearities, the EKF linearises the two non-linear equations using the first term of the Taylor series and then treats the problem as the standard linear Kalman filter problem.
[src:radar-systems/radar-tracker] Although conceptually simple, the filter can easily diverge (i.e., gradually perform more and more badly) if the state estimate about which the equations are linearised is poor.
[src:radar-systems/radar-tracker] The unscented Kalman filter and particle filters are attempts to overcome the problem of linearising the equations.
[src:radar-systems/radar-tracker] The UKF attempts to improve on the EKF by removing the need to linearise the measurement and state equations.
[src:radar-systems/radar-tracker] It avoids linearization by representing the mean and covariance information in the form of a set of points, called sigma points.
[src:radar-systems/radar-tracker] These points, which represent a distribution with specified mean and covariance, are then propagated directly through the non-linear equations, and the resulting updated samples are then used to calculate a new mean and variance.
[src:radar-systems/radar-tracker] This approach then suffers none of the problems of divergence due to poor linearisation and yet retains the overall computational simplicity of the EKF.
[src:radar-systems/radar-tracker] The particle filter could be considered as a generalisation of the UKF.
[src:radar-systems/radar-tracker] It makes no assumptions about the distributions of the errors in the filter and neither does it require the equations to be linear.
[src:radar-systems/radar-tracker] Instead it generates a large number of random potential states ("particles") and then propagates this "cloud of particles" through the equations, resulting in a different distribution of particles at the output.
[src:radar-systems/radar-tracker] The resulting distribution of particles can then be used to calculate a mean or variance, or whatever other statistical measure is required.
[src:radar-systems/radar-tracker] The resulting statistics are used to generate the random sample of particles for the next iteration.
[src:radar-systems/radar-tracker] The particle filter is notable in its ability to handle multi-modal distributions (i.e., distributions where the probability density function (PDF) has more than one peak).
[src:radar-systems/radar-tracker] However, it is computationally very intensive and is currently unsuitable for most real-world, real-time applications.
[src:radar-systems/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] To create a SAR image, successive pulses of radio waves are transmitted to "illuminate" a target scene, and the echo of each pulse is received and recorded.
[src:radar-systems/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] The pulses are transmitted and the echoes received using a single beam-forming antenna, with wavelengths of a meter down to several millimeters.
[src:radar-systems/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] As the SAR device on board the aircraft or spacecraft moves, the antenna location relative to the target changes with time.
[src:radar-systems/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] Signal processing of the successive recorded radar echoes allows the combining of the recordings from these multiple antenna positions.
[src:radar-systems/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] This process forms the *synthetic antenna aperture* and allows the creation of higher-resolution images than would otherwise be possible with a given physical antenna.
[src:radar-systems/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] SAR is capable of high-resolution remote sensing, independent of flight altitude, and independent of weather, as SAR can select frequencies to avoid weather-caused signal attenuation.
[src:radar-systems/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] SAR has day and night imaging capability as illumination is provided by the SAR.
[src:radar-systems/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] SAR images have wide applications in remote sensing and mapping of surfaces of the Earth and other planets.
[src:radar-systems/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] Examples include topography, oceanography, glaciology, geology (for example, terrain discrimination and subsurface imaging).
[src:radar-systems/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] SAR can also be used in forestry to determine forest height, biomass, and deforestation.
[src:radar-systems/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] Volcano and earthquake monitoring use differential interferometry.
[src:radar-systems/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] SAR can also be applied for monitoring civil infrastructure stability such as bridges.
[src:radar-systems/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] SAR is useful in environment monitoring such as oil spills, flooding, urban growth, and military surveillance: including strategic policy and tactical assessment.
[src:radar-systems/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] SAR can be implemented as inverse SAR by observing a moving target over a substantial time with a stationary antenna.
[src:radar-systems/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] A *synthetic-aperture radar* is an imaging radar mounted on a moving platform.
[src:radar-systems/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] It is based on the fact that "radar reflections from discrete objects in a passing radar beam field each [have] a minute Doppler, or speed, shift relative to the antenna".
[src:radar-systems/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] In order to realise this concept, electromagnetic waves are transmitted sequentially, the echoes are collected and the system electronics digitizes and stores the data for subsequent processing.
[src:radar-systems/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] As transmission and reception occur at different times, they map to different small positions.
[src:radar-systems/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] The well ordered combination of the received signals builds a virtual aperture that is much longer than the physical antenna width.
[src:radar-systems/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] That is the source of the term "synthetic aperture," giving it the property of an imaging radar.
[src:radar-systems/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] The range direction is perpendicular to the flight track and perpendicular to the azimuth direction, which is also known as the *along-track* direction because it is in line with the position of the object within the antenna's field of view.
[src:radar-systems/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] The 3D processing is done in two stages.
[src:radar-systems/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] The azimuth and range direction are focused for the generation of 2D (azimuth-range) high-resolution images, after which a digital elevation model (DEM) is used to measure the phase differences between complex images, which is determined from different look angles to recover the height information.
[src:radar-systems/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] This height information, along with the azimuth-range coordinates provided by 2-D SAR focusing, gives the third dimension, which is the elevation.
[src:radar-systems/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] The first step requires only standard processing algorithms, for the second step, additional pre-processing such as image co-registration and phase calibration is used.
[src:radar-systems/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] In addition, multiple baselines can be used to extend 3D imaging to the *time dimension*.
[src:radar-systems/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] 4D and multi-D SAR imaging allows imaging of complex scenarios, such as urban areas, and has improved performance with respect to classical interferometric techniques such as persistent scatterer interferometry (PSI).
[src:radar-systems/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] SAR algorithms model the scene as a set of point targets that do not interact with each other (the Born approximation).
[src:radar-systems/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] While the details of various SAR algorithms differ, SAR processing in each case is the application of a matched filter to the raw data, for each pixel in the output image, where the matched filter coefficients are the response from a single isolated point target.
[src:radar-systems/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] In the early days of SAR processing, the raw data was recorded on film and the postprocessing by matched filter was implemented optically using lenses of conical, cylindrical and spherical shape.
[src:radar-systems/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] The Range-Doppler algorithm is an example of a more recent approach.
[src:radar-systems/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] Synthetic-aperture radar determines the 3D reflectivity from measured SAR data.
[src:radar-systems/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] It is basically a spectrum estimation, because for a specific cell of an image, the complex-value SAR measurements of the SAR image stack are a sampled version of the Fourier transform of reflectivity in elevation direction, but the Fourier transform is irregular.
[src:radar-systems/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] Thus the spectral estimation techniques are used to improve the resolution and reduce speckle compared to the results of conventional Fourier transform SAR imaging techniques.
[src:radar-systems/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] FFT (Fast Fourier Transform i.e., periodogram or matched filter) is one such method, which is used in the majority of the spectral estimation algorithms, and there are many fast algorithms for computing the multidimensional discrete Fourier transform.
[src:radar-systems/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] Computational *Kronecker-core array algebra* is a popular algorithm used as new variant of FFT algorithms for the processing in multidimensional synthetic-aperture radar (SAR) systems.
[src:radar-systems/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] This algorithm uses a study of theoretical properties of input/output data indexing sets and groups of permutations.
[src:radar-systems/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] A branch of finite multi-dimensional linear algebra is used to identify similarities and differences among various FFT algorithm variants and to create new variants.
[src:radar-systems/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] Each multidimensional DFT computation is expressed in matrix form.
[src:radar-systems/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] The multidimensional DFT matrix, in turn, is disintegrated into a set of factors, called functional primitives, which are individually identified with an underlying software/hardware computational design.
[src:radar-systems/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] The FFT implementation is essentially a realization of the mapping of the mathematical framework through generation of the variants and executing matrix operations.
[src:radar-systems/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] The performance of this implementation may vary from machine to machine, and the objective is to identify on which machine it performs best.
[src:radar-systems/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] The Capon spectral method, also called the minimum-variance method, is a multidimensional array-processing technique.
[src:radar-systems/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] Therefore, it passes a 2D sinusoid at a given frequency without distortion while minimizing the variance of the noise of the resulting image.
[src:radar-systems/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] The purpose is to compute the spectral estimate efficiently.
[src:radar-systems/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] where *R* is the covariance matrix, and $a_{\omega _{1},\omega _{2}}^{*}$ is the 2D complex-conjugate transpose of the Fourier vector.
[src:radar-systems/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] The computation of this equation over all frequencies is time-consuming.
[src:radar-systems/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] It is seen that the forward–backward Capon estimator yields better estimation than the forward-only classical Capon approach.
[src:radar-systems/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] The main reason behind this is that while the forward–backward Capon uses both the forward and backward data vectors to obtain the estimate of the covariance matrix, the forward-only Capon uses only the forward data vectors to estimate the covariance matrix.
[src:radar-systems/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] The APES (amplitude and phase estimation) method is also a matched-filter-bank method, which assumes that the phase history data is a sum of 2D sinusoids in noise.
[src:radar-systems/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] Obtaining the spectrum estimate for $\omega \in [0,2\pi )$ from the filtered data.
[src:radar-systems/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] Empirically, the APES method results in wider spectral peaks than the Capon method, but more accurate spectral estimates for amplitude in SAR.
[src:radar-systems/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] In the Capon method, although the spectral peaks are narrower than the APES, the sidelobes are higher than that for the APES.
[src:radar-systems/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] As a result, the estimate for the amplitude is expected to be less accurate for the Capon method than for the APES method.
[src:radar-systems/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] The APES method requires about 1.5 times more computation than the Capon method.
[src:radar-systems/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] SAMV method is a parameter-free sparse signal reconstruction based algorithm.
[src:radar-systems/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] It achieves super-resolution and is robust to highly correlated signals.
[src:radar-systems/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] The name emphasizes its basis on the asymptotically minimum variance (AMV) criterion.
[src:radar-systems/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] It is a powerful tool for the recovery of both the amplitude and frequency characteristics of multiple highly correlated sources in challenging environment (e.g., limited number of snapshots, low signal-to-noise ratio).
[src:radar-systems/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] Applications include synthetic-aperture radar imaging and various source localization.
[src:radar-systems/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] SAMV method is capable of achieving resolution higher than some established parametric methods, e.g., MUSIC, especially with highly correlated signals.
[src:radar-systems/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] Computational complexity of the SAMV method is higher due to its iterative procedure.
[src:radar-systems/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] This subspace decomposition method separates the eigenvectors of the autocovariance matrix into those corresponding to signals and to clutter.
[src:radar-systems/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] where ⊗ denotes the Kronecker product of the two vectors.
[src:radar-systems/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] MUSIC detects frequencies in a signal by performing an eigen decomposition on the covariance matrix of a data vector of the samples obtained from the samples of the received signal.
[src:radar-systems/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] When all of the eigenvectors are included in the clutter subspace (model order = 0) the EV method becomes identical to the Capon method.
[src:radar-systems/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] Thus the determination of model order is critical to operation of the EV method.
[src:radar-systems/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] The eigenvalue of the R matrix decides whether its corresponding eigenvector corresponds to the clutter or to the signal subspace.
[src:radar-systems/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] The MUSIC method is considered to be a poor performer in SAR applications.
[src:radar-systems/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] This method uses a constant instead of the clutter subspace.
[src:radar-systems/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] In this method, the denominator is equated to zero when a sinusoidal signal corresponding to a point in the SAR image is in alignment to one of the signal subspace eigenvectors which is the peak in image estimate.
[src:radar-systems/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] Thus this method does not accurately represent the scattering intensity at each point, but show the particular points of the image.
[src:radar-systems/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] Backprojection Algorithm has two methods: *Time-domain Backprojection* and *Frequency-domain Backprojection*.
[src:radar-systems/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] The time-domain Backprojection has more advantages over frequency-domain and thus, is more preferred.
[src:radar-systems/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] The time-domain Backprojection forms images or spectrums by matching the data acquired from the radar and as per what it expects to receive.
[src:radar-systems/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] It can be considered as an ideal matched-filter for synthetic-aperture radar.
[src:radar-systems/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] There is no need of having a different motion compensation step due to its quality of handling non-ideal motion/sampling.
[src:radar-systems/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] It can also be used for various imaging geometries.
[src:radar-systems/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] In GEO-SAR, to focus specially on the relative moving track, the backprojection algorithm works very well.
[src:radar-systems/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] It uses the concept of Azimuth Processing in the time domain.
[src:radar-systems/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] For the satellite-ground geometry, GEO-SAR plays a significant role.
[src:radar-systems/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] The procedure of this concept is elaborated as follows.
[src:radar-systems/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] The range of the data is then compressed, using the concept of "Matched Filtering" for every segment/sub-aperture created.
[src:radar-systems/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] It is given by- ${\textstyle s(t,\tau )=\exp \left(-j\cdot {\frac {4\pi }{\lambda }}\cdot R(t)\right)\cdot \operatorname {sinc} \left(\tau -{\frac {2}{c}}\cdot R(t)\right)}$ where *τ* is the range time, *t* is the azimuthal time, *λ* is the wavelength, *c* is the speed of light.
[src:radar-systems/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] Accuracy in the "Range Migration Curve" is achieved by range interpolation.
[src:radar-systems/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] The pixel locations of the ground in the image is dependent on the satellite–ground geometry model.
[src:radar-systems/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] Grid-division is now done as per the azimuth time.
[src:radar-systems/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] Calculations for the "slant range" (range between the antenna's phase center and the point on the ground) are done for every azimuth time using coordinate transformations.
[src:radar-systems/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] Azimuth Compression is done after the previous step.
[src:radar-systems/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] Step 5 and 6 are repeated for every pixel, to cover every pixel, and conduct the procedure on every sub-aperture.
[src:radar-systems/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] Lastly, all the sub-apertures of the image created throughout, are superimposed onto each other and the ultimate HD image is generated.
[src:radar-systems/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] Capon and APES can yield more accurate spectral estimates with much lower sidelobes and more narrow spectral peaks than the fast Fourier transform (FFT) method, which is also a special case of the FIR filtering approaches.
[src:radar-systems/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] It is seen that although the APES algorithm gives slightly wider spectral peaks than the Capon method, the former yields more accurate overall spectral estimates than the latter and the FFT method.
[src:radar-systems/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] FFT method is fast and simple but have larger sidelobes.
[src:radar-systems/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] Capon has high resolution but high computational complexity.
[src:radar-systems/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] EV also has high resolution and high computational complexity.
[src:radar-systems/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] APES has higher resolution, faster than capon and EV but high computational complexity.
[src:radar-systems/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] MUSIC method is not generally suitable for SAR imaging, as whitening the clutter eigenvalues destroys the spatial inhomogeneities associated with terrain clutter or other diffuse scattering in SAR imagery.
[src:radar-systems/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] But it offers higher frequency resolution in the resulting power spectral density (PSD) than the fast Fourier transform (FFT)-based methods.
[src:radar-systems/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] The backprojection algorithm is computationally expensive.
[src:radar-systems/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] It is specifically attractive for sensors that are wideband, wide-angle, and/or have long coherent apertures with substantial off-track motion.
[src:radar-systems/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] SAR requires that echo captures be taken at multiple antenna positions.
[src:radar-systems/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] The more captures taken (at different antenna locations) the more reliable the target characterization.
[src:radar-systems/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] Multiple captures can be obtained by moving a single antenna to different locations, by placing multiple stationary antennas at different locations, or combinations thereof.
[src:radar-systems/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] The advantage of a single moving antenna is that it can be easily placed in any number of positions to provide any number of monostatic waveforms.
[src:radar-systems/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] For example, an antenna mounted on an airplane takes many captures per second as the plane travels.
[src:radar-systems/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] The principal advantages of multiple static antennas are that a moving target can be characterized (assuming the capture electronics are fast enough), that no vehicle or motion machinery is necessary, and that antenna positions need not be derived from other, sometimes unreliable, information.
[src:radar-systems/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] (One problem with SAR aboard an airplane is knowing precise antenna positions as the plane travels).
[src:radar-systems/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] For multiple static antennas, all combinations of monostatic and multistatic radar waveform captures are possible.
[src:radar-systems/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] Note, however, that it is not advantageous to capture a waveform for each of both transmission directions for a given pair of antennas, because those waveforms will be identical.
[src:radar-systems/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] where *N* is the number of unique antenna positions.
[src:radar-systems/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] It may be orthogonal to the flight path, or it may be squinted slightly forward or backward.
[src:radar-systems/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] When the antenna aperture travels along the flight path, a signal is transmitted at a rate equal to the pulse repetition frequency (PRF).
[src:radar-systems/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] The lower boundary of the PRF is determined by the Doppler bandwidth of the radar.
[src:radar-systems/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] The backscatter of each of these signals is commutatively added on a pixel-by-pixel basis to attain the fine azimuth resolution desired in radar imagery.
[src:radar-systems/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] where $\Delta \theta _{a}$ is the angle formed between the beginning and end of the imaging, as shown in the diagram of spotlight imaging and $r_{0}$ is the range distance.
[src:radar-systems/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] The spotlight mode gives better resolution albeit for a smaller ground patch.
[src:radar-systems/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] In this mode, the illuminating radar beam is steered continually as the aircraft moves, so that it illuminates the same patch over a longer period of time.
[src:radar-systems/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] This mode is not a traditional continuous-strip imaging mode; however, it has high azimuth resolution.
[src:radar-systems/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] A technical explanation of spotlight SAR from first principles is offered in.
[src:radar-systems/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] While operating as a scan mode SAR, the antenna beam sweeps periodically and thus cover much larger area than the spotlight and stripmap modes.
[src:radar-systems/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] However, the azimuth resolution become much lower than the stripmap mode due to the decreased azimuth bandwidth.
[src:radar-systems/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] Clearly there is a balance achieved between the azimuth resolution and the scan area of SAR.
[src:radar-systems/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] Here, the synthetic aperture is shared between the sub swaths, and it is not in direct contact within one subswath.
[src:radar-systems/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] Mosaic operation is required in azimuth and range directions to join the azimuth bursts and the range sub-swaths.
[src:radar-systems/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] Different materials reflect radar waves with different intensities, but anisotropic materials such as grass often reflect different polarizations with different intensities.
[src:radar-systems/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] Some materials will also convert one polarization into another.
[src:radar-systems/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] By emitting a mixture of polarizations and using receiving antennas with a specific polarization, several images can be collected from the same series of pulses.
[src:radar-systems/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] Frequently three such RX-TX polarizations (HH-pol, VV-pol, VH-pol) are used as the three color channels in a synthesized image.
[src:radar-systems/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] This is what has been done in the picture at right.
[src:radar-systems/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] Interpretation of the resulting colors requires significant testing of known materials.
[src:radar-systems/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] New developments in polarimetry include using the changes in the random polarization returns of some surfaces (such as grass or sand) and between two images of the same location at different times to determine where changes not visible to optical systems occurred.
[src:radar-systems/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] Examples include subterranean tunneling or paths of vehicles driving through the area being imaged.
[src:radar-systems/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] Enhanced SAR sea oil slick observation has been developed by appropriate physical modelling and use of fully polarimetric and dual-polarimetric measurements.
[src:radar-systems/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] SAR polarimetry is a technique used for deriving qualitative and quantitative physical information for land, snow and ice, ocean and urban applications based on the measurement and exploration of the polarimetric properties of man-made and natural scatterers.
[src:radar-systems/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] *Terrain* and *land use* classification is one of the most important applications of polarimetric synthetic-aperture radar (PolSAR).
[src:radar-systems/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] SAR polarimetry uses a scattering matrix (S) to identify the scattering behavior of objects after an interaction with electromagnetic wave.
[src:radar-systems/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] The matrix is represented by a combination of horizontal and vertical polarization states of transmitted and received signals.
[src:radar-systems/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] where, HH is for horizontal transmit and horizontal receive, VV is for vertical transmit and vertical receive, HV is for horizontal transmit and vertical receive, and VH for vertical transmit and horizontal receive.
[src:radar-systems/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] The first two of these polarization combinations are referred to as like-polarized (or co-polarized), because the transmit and receive polarizations are the same.
[src:radar-systems/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] The last two combinations are referred to as cross-polarized because the transmit and receive polarizations are orthogonal to one another.
[src:radar-systems/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] The three-component scattering power model by Freeman and Durden is successfully used for the decomposition of a PolSAR image, applying the reflection symmetry condition using covariance matrix.
[src:radar-systems/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] The method is based on simple physical scattering mechanisms (surface scattering, double-bounce scattering, and volume scattering).
[src:radar-systems/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] The advantage of this scattering model is that it is simple and easy to implement for image processing.
[src:radar-systems/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] There are 2 major approaches for a 3 $\times$ 3 polarimetric matrix decomposition.
[src:radar-systems/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] One is the lexicographic covariance matrix approach based on physically measurable parameters, and the other is the Pauli decomposition which is a coherent decomposition matrix.
